1
00:00:56,389 --> 00:00:58,934
Saturday
November 12, 1955

2
00:00:59,017 --> 00:01:01,895
10:03 PM

3
00:01:22,791 --> 00:01:24,125
Doc!

4
00:02:25,687 --> 00:02:28,189
Doc! Doc! Doc!

5
00:02:28,231 --> 00:02:29,983
- Doc! Doc!
-What?

6
00:02:31,735 --> 00:02:34,070
Okay, relax, Doc. It's
me. It's me! It's Marty.

7
00:02:34,154 --> 00:02:36,614
No, it can't be.
I just sent you back to the future.

8
00:02:36,698 --> 00:02:40,035
Yeah. No, I know. You did send me
back to the future, but I'm back.

9
00:02:40,076 --> 00:02:42,245
I'm back from the future.

10
00:02:45,457 --> 00:02:47,083
Great Scott!

11
00:05:03,261 --> 00:05:04,846
Hey, kids, what time is it?

12
00:05:04,929 --> 00:05:07,515
Howdy Doody time!

13
00:05:09,267 --> 00:05:11,060
Great Scott!

14
00:05:11,144 --> 00:05:14,606
It's Howdy Doody Time

15
00:05:14,689 --> 00:05:20,361
Bob Smith and Howdy Do
Say Howdy Do to you

16
00:05:20,445 --> 00:05:22,197
Howdy Doody time?

17
00:05:27,368 --> 00:05:31,998
Date. Sunday, November 13, 1955. 7:01 a.m.

18
00:05:32,040 --> 00:05:35,460
Last night's time travel experiment
was apparently a complete success.

19
00:05:35,543 --> 00:05:38,171
Lightning struck the clock tower
at precisely 10:04 p.m.

20
00:05:38,213 --> 00:05:41,049
sending the necessary 1.21 gigawatts
into the time vehicle,

21
00:05:41,132 --> 00:05:45,803
which vanished in a brilliant flash of
light leaving a pair of fire trails behind.

22
00:05:45,887 --> 00:05:48,014
I, therefore, assume
that Marty and the time vehicle

23
00:05:48,056 --> 00:05:51,893
were transported forward through time
into the year 1985.

24
00:05:51,935 --> 00:05:56,064
After that...
After that, I can't recall what happened.

25
00:05:56,147 --> 00:05:58,942
In fact, I don't even remember
how I got home.

26
00:05:59,025 --> 00:06:02,612
Perhaps the gigawatt discharge coupled
with the temporal displacement field

27
00:06:02,695 --> 00:06:06,115
generated by the time vehicle caused
a disruption of my own brain waves

28
00:06:06,199 --> 00:06:09,160
resulting in a condition
of momentary amnesia.

29
00:06:09,244 --> 00:06:12,580
Indeed, I now recall that moments
after the time vehicle disappeared

30
00:06:12,622 --> 00:06:13,665
into the future,

31
00:06:13,748 --> 00:06:17,835
I saw a vision of Marty saying
he had come back from the future.

32
00:06:17,919 --> 00:06:18,920
Hey, Doc!

33
00:06:18,962 --> 00:06:20,296
Undoubtedly, this was some sort
of residual image...

34
00:06:20,380 --> 00:06:21,422
Doc.

35
00:06:27,428 --> 00:06:30,723
Doc, calm down, okay. Just calm down.
It's me. It's Marty.

36
00:06:30,765 --> 00:06:33,309
No, it can't be you!
I sent you back to the future!

37
00:06:33,393 --> 00:06:34,519
That's right, Doc. That's right,

38
00:06:34,602 --> 00:06:36,521
but I came back again.
I came back from the future.

39
00:06:36,604 --> 00:06:38,856
Don't you remember last night?
You fainted. I brought you home.

40
00:06:38,940 --> 00:06:41,526
This can't be happening! You can't be here!

41
00:06:41,609 --> 00:06:45,071
It doesn't make sense for you to be here!
I refuse to even believe that you are here!

42
00:06:45,113 --> 00:06:49,659
Doc, I am here, and it does make sense.
Look, I came back to 1955 again with you,

43
00:06:49,742 --> 00:06:52,620
the you from 1985,
'cause we had to get a book from Biff!

44
00:06:52,662 --> 00:06:55,540
So once I got the book back,
you, that is the you from 1985,

45
00:06:55,623 --> 00:06:57,417
were in the DeLorean,
and it got struck by lightning,

46
00:06:57,458 --> 00:06:59,586
and you got sent back to 1885!

47
00:06:59,627 --> 00:07:00,962
1885?

48
00:07:03,214 --> 00:07:06,175
It's a very interesting story, future boy,

49
00:07:06,259 --> 00:07:08,970
but there's just one little thing
that doesn't make sense.

50
00:07:09,053 --> 00:07:13,891
If the me of the future is now in the past,
how could you possibly know about it?

51
00:07:13,975 --> 00:07:15,393
You sent me a letter.

52
00:07:15,476 --> 00:07:17,645
"Dear Marty, if my
calculations are correct,

53
00:07:17,729 --> 00:07:19,680
"you will receive
this letter immediately

54
00:07:19,692 --> 00:07:21,983
after you saw the
DeLorean struck by lightning.

55
00:07:22,066 --> 00:07:24,902
"First, let me assure you
that I'm alive and well.

56
00:07:24,986 --> 00:07:29,032
"I've been living happily
these past eight months in the year 1885.

57
00:07:29,115 --> 00:07:31,909
"The lightning bolt that hit the DeLorean
caused a gigawatt overload

58
00:07:31,993 --> 00:07:35,246
"which scrambled the time circuits,
activated the Flux Capacitor,

59
00:07:35,330 --> 00:07:38,249
"and sent me back to 1885.

60
00:07:38,333 --> 00:07:42,170
"The overload shorted out the time circuits
and destroyed the flying circuits.

61
00:07:42,211 --> 00:07:44,881
"Unfortunately, the
car will never fly again."

62
00:07:44,964 --> 00:07:46,299
It actually flew?

63
00:07:46,341 --> 00:07:49,594
Yeah, we had a hover conversion done
in the early 21st century.

64
00:07:49,677 --> 00:07:51,596
Incredible!

65
00:07:51,679 --> 00:07:54,766
"I set myself up as a blacksmith as a front

66
00:07:54,849 --> 00:07:58,186
"while I attempted to repair the damage
to the time circuits.

67
00:07:58,269 --> 00:08:00,104
"Unfortunately, this proved impossible,

68
00:08:00,188 --> 00:08:05,068
"because suitable replacement parts
will not be invented until 1947.

69
00:08:05,151 --> 00:08:10,114
"However, I've gotten quite adept
at shoeing horses and fixing wagons."

70
00:08:11,240 --> 00:08:14,202
1885! Amazing!

71
00:08:14,285 --> 00:08:17,538
I actually end up as a blacksmith
in the Old West.

72
00:08:17,955 --> 00:08:19,332
Pretty heavy, huh?

73
00:08:19,374 --> 00:08:22,377
"I have buried the DeLorean
in the abandoned Delgado Mine

74
00:08:22,418 --> 00:08:27,048
"adjacent to the old Boot Hill Cemetery
as shown on the enclosed map.

75
00:08:27,090 --> 00:08:32,178
"Hopefully, it should remain undisturbed
and preserved until you uncover it in 1955.

76
00:08:33,429 --> 00:08:36,557
"Inside, you will find repair instructions.

77
00:08:37,225 --> 00:08:40,728
"My 1955 counterpart..." That's me.

78
00:08:40,812 --> 00:08:44,982
"...should have no problem repairing it so
that you can drive it back to the future.

79
00:08:45,066 --> 00:08:49,028
"Once you have returned to 1985,
destroy the time machine."

80
00:08:49,070 --> 00:08:53,783
- Destroy it?
-Yeah. Well, it's a long story, Doc.

81
00:08:53,866 --> 00:08:58,871
"Do not, I repeat, do not attempt
to come back here to get me.

82
00:08:59,414 --> 00:09:03,584
"I am perfectly happy living in
the fresh air and wide-open spaces.

83
00:09:03,626 --> 00:09:06,129
"And I fear that unnecessary time travel

84
00:09:06,212 --> 00:09:09,924
"only risks further disruption
of the space-time continuum.

85
00:09:10,007 --> 00:09:13,469
"And please take care of Einstein for me."

86
00:09:15,012 --> 00:09:16,139
Einstein?

87
00:09:16,222 --> 00:09:20,643
He's your dog, Doc. Einstein is
what you call your dog in 1985.

88
00:09:23,604 --> 00:09:25,606
"I know you will give him a good home.

89
00:09:25,690 --> 00:09:29,694
"Remember to walk him twice a day
and that he only likes canned dog food.

90
00:09:29,777 --> 00:09:32,989
"These are my wishes.
Please respect them and follow them.

91
00:09:33,072 --> 00:09:37,452
"And so, Marty, I now say farewell
and wish you Godspeed.

92
00:09:37,535 --> 00:09:40,121
"You've been a good, kind,
and loyal friend to me,

93
00:09:40,163 --> 00:09:42,874
"and you made a real difference in my life.

94
00:09:42,957 --> 00:09:47,462
"I will always treasure our relationship
and think on you with fond memories,

95
00:09:47,503 --> 00:09:50,631
"warm feelings,
and a special place in my heart.

96
00:09:52,341 --> 00:09:56,179
"Your friend in time, Doc Emmett L. Brown.

97
00:09:56,262 --> 00:09:58,890
"September 1st, 1885."

98
00:10:00,892 --> 00:10:02,810
I never knew I could write
anything so touching.

99
00:10:02,852 --> 00:10:04,604
I know. I know, Doc. It's beautiful.

100
00:10:07,648 --> 00:10:10,860
It's all right, Copernicus.
Everything is gonna be fine.

101
00:10:10,943 --> 00:10:13,821
I'm sorry, Doc.
It's all my fault you're stuck back there.

102
00:10:13,905 --> 00:10:15,490
I never should've let Biff get to me.

103
00:10:15,573 --> 00:10:18,493
There are plenty worse places to be
than the Old West.

104
00:10:18,534 --> 00:10:20,119
I could have ended up in the Dark Ages.

105
00:10:20,161 --> 00:10:23,956
They probably would have burned me
at the stake as a heretic or something.

106
00:10:23,998 --> 00:10:25,625
Let's look at the map.

107
00:10:25,666 --> 00:10:30,463
All right, according to this, the time
vehicle is sealed off in a side tunnel.

108
00:10:30,505 --> 00:10:32,006
We may have to blast.

109
00:10:45,186 --> 00:10:46,354
Whoa!

110
00:10:47,271 --> 00:10:49,440
I think you woke up
the dead with that blast.

111
00:10:49,524 --> 00:10:52,193
Take this camera.
I want to document everything!

112
00:10:54,612 --> 00:10:58,533
This reminds me of the time I
attempted to reach the center of the Earth.

113
00:10:58,574 --> 00:11:01,118
I'd been reading my favorite author,
Jules Verne.

114
00:11:01,202 --> 00:11:04,747
I spent weeks preparing that expedition.
I didn't even get this far.

115
00:11:04,831 --> 00:11:07,375
Of course, I was only 12 at the time.

116
00:11:07,458 --> 00:11:10,106
You know, it was
the writings of Jules

117
00:11:10,118 --> 00:11:13,256
Verne that had a
profound effect on my life.

118
00:11:13,339 --> 00:11:17,093
It was when I was 11 that I first read
Twenty Thousand Leagues Under the Sea.

119
00:11:17,176 --> 00:11:22,223
It was then that I realized
that I must devote my life to science.

120
00:11:22,265 --> 00:11:24,725
Doc, check it out. Look at this.

121
00:11:28,479 --> 00:11:30,064
My initials!

122
00:11:30,106 --> 00:11:32,233
Just like in
Journey to the Center of the Earth!

123
00:11:32,358 --> 00:11:34,110
That means the time machine
must be right through this wall!

124
00:11:56,757 --> 00:12:02,013
It's been buried in here for
70 years, two months, and 13 days.

125
00:12:02,096 --> 00:12:03,431
Astounding!

126
00:12:03,514 --> 00:12:05,433
"As you can see, the lightning bolt

127
00:12:05,516 --> 00:12:08,644
"shorted out the time circuit
control microchip.

128
00:12:10,813 --> 00:12:14,025
- "The attached..."
-Schematic.

129
00:12:14,108 --> 00:12:18,237
"Schematic diagram will allow you
to build a replacement unit

130
00:12:18,279 --> 00:12:22,617
"with 1955 components, thus restoring
the time machine to perfect working order."

131
00:12:22,700 --> 00:12:27,163
Unbelievable that this little piece of junk
could be such a big problem.

132
00:12:29,707 --> 00:12:32,668
No wonder this circuit failed.
It says, "Made in Japan."

133
00:12:34,462 --> 00:12:37,965
What do you mean, Doc?
All the best stuff is made in Japan.

134
00:12:40,051 --> 00:12:41,427
Unbelievable!

135
00:12:47,475 --> 00:12:52,104
You know, when I was a kid,
I always wanted to be a cowboy.

136
00:12:53,147 --> 00:12:55,691
And now, knowing I'm gonna spend
my future in the past,

137
00:12:55,775 --> 00:12:59,654
it sounds like a wonderful way
to spend my retirement years.

138
00:12:59,695 --> 00:13:02,573
It just occurred to me, Marty,
since I end up in 1885,

139
00:13:02,657 --> 00:13:04,784
perhaps I'm now in the history books.

140
00:13:04,825 --> 00:13:06,702
I wonder.

141
00:13:06,786 --> 00:13:10,873
Could I go to the library and look
myself up in the old newspaper archives?

142
00:13:10,957 --> 00:13:13,334
I don't know, Doc. You're the one
that's always saying, you know,

143
00:13:13,417 --> 00:13:15,461
it's not good to know too much
about your own destiny.

144
00:13:15,503 --> 00:13:19,006
You're right, Marty.
I know too much already.

145
00:13:19,090 --> 00:13:24,303
Better that I not attempt to uncover
the circumstances of my own future.

146
00:13:24,345 --> 00:13:27,348
Copernicus. Come on, boy!

147
00:13:27,890 --> 00:13:30,184
I'll get him, Doc. Copernicus!

148
00:13:31,352 --> 00:13:34,230
Copernicus, come on. Let's go home, boy.

149
00:13:35,147 --> 00:13:37,149
What's wrong?

150
00:13:37,191 --> 00:13:40,528
What's wrong, Copernicus? Come on.

151
00:13:40,611 --> 00:13:43,239
Come on, let's go home. Come on. Come on.

152
00:13:46,993 --> 00:13:50,079
Doc! Doc! Come here!

153
00:13:50,162 --> 00:13:51,372
Quick!

154
00:13:53,249 --> 00:13:56,752
What's wrong, Marty?
You look like you've seen a ghost.

155
00:13:56,836 --> 00:13:58,963
You're not far off, Doc.

156
00:14:03,217 --> 00:14:05,177
Great Scott!

157
00:14:05,219 --> 00:14:06,387
Check this out.

158
00:14:06,470 --> 00:14:11,392
"Died September 7th, 1885." That's
one week after you wrote the letter!

159
00:14:11,767 --> 00:14:15,104
"Erected in eternal memory
by his beloved Clara."

160
00:14:15,521 --> 00:14:17,023
Who the hell is Clara?

161
00:14:17,064 --> 00:14:18,899
Marty, please don't stand there!

162
00:14:18,941 --> 00:14:20,526
Oh! Right. Sorry.

163
00:14:20,568 --> 00:14:22,570
I gotta get another picture.

164
00:14:23,904 --> 00:14:27,992
"Shot in the back
by Buford Tannen over a matter of $80"?

165
00:14:28,576 --> 00:14:30,828
What kind of a future do you call that?

166
00:14:31,912 --> 00:14:34,373
"Buford Tannen
was a notorious gunman

167
00:14:34,415 --> 00:14:37,251
"whose short temper
and a tendency to drool

168
00:14:37,293 --> 00:14:39,253
"earned him the nickname Mad Dog.

169
00:14:39,295 --> 00:14:42,840
"He was quick on the trigger
and bragged that he had killed 12 men

170
00:14:42,923 --> 00:14:44,759
"not including Indians or Chinamen."

171
00:14:44,800 --> 00:14:47,636
- Does it mention me? Am I one of the 12?
-Just a minute.

172
00:14:47,720 --> 00:14:49,513
"However this claim
cannot be substantiated,

173
00:14:49,597 --> 00:14:53,100
"since precise records were not kept
after Tannen shot a newspaper editor

174
00:14:53,142 --> 00:14:55,978
"who printed an unfavorable story
about him in 1884."

175
00:14:56,062 --> 00:14:58,147
- That's why we can't find anything.
- Look.

176
00:14:59,732 --> 00:15:02,610
William McFly and family. Your relatives?

177
00:15:02,693 --> 00:15:07,823
My great-grandfather's name
was William. That's him. Good-looking guy.

178
00:15:09,867 --> 00:15:12,244
McFlys, but no Browns.

179
00:15:12,286 --> 00:15:14,497
Well, maybe it was a mistake, Doc.
Maybe that grave wasn't yours.

180
00:15:14,580 --> 00:15:16,874
There could've been
another Emmett Brown back in 1885.

181
00:15:16,957 --> 00:15:17,958
- No.
-I don't know.

182
00:15:18,042 --> 00:15:19,126
Did you have any relatives here back then?

183
00:15:19,210 --> 00:15:21,253
The Browns didn't come
to Hill Valley until 1908.

184
00:15:21,295 --> 00:15:22,963
And then they were the von Brauns.

185
00:15:23,005 --> 00:15:25,549
My father changed our name
during the First World War.

186
00:15:25,633 --> 00:15:26,759
Doc, look.

187
00:15:29,053 --> 00:15:32,056
Great Scott, it's me!

188
00:15:32,139 --> 00:15:35,017
Then it is true, all of it.

189
00:15:35,101 --> 00:15:38,562
It is me who goes back there and gets shot.

190
00:15:38,646 --> 00:15:41,065
It's not gonna happen, Doc.

191
00:15:41,148 --> 00:15:44,318
After you fix the time circuits
and put new tires on the DeLorean,

192
00:15:44,401 --> 00:15:47,863
I'm going back to 1885,
and I'm bringing you home.

193
00:15:59,375 --> 00:16:01,293
The clothes fit?

194
00:16:01,335 --> 00:16:04,880
Yeah, everything except
the boots, Doc. They're kind of tight.

195
00:16:04,964 --> 00:16:07,341
I don't know.
Are you sure this stuff is authentic?

196
00:16:07,383 --> 00:16:10,719
Of course. Haven't you ever seen a Western?

197
00:16:11,512 --> 00:16:13,681
Yeah, I have, Doc.

198
00:16:13,764 --> 00:16:16,642
Clint Eastwood
never wore anything like this.

199
00:16:17,893 --> 00:16:18,809
Clint who?

200
00:16:18,821 --> 00:16:21,605
That's right. You
haven't heard of him yet.

201
00:16:21,689 --> 00:16:23,524
Marty, you have to wear the boots.

202
00:16:23,607 --> 00:16:26,318
You can't wear those futuristic things
back in 1885.

203
00:16:26,360 --> 00:16:28,237
You shouldn't even be wearing them
here in 1955.

204
00:16:28,320 --> 00:16:30,865
All right, Doc. Look, as soon as I
get there, I'll put them on. I promise.

205
00:16:30,906 --> 00:16:33,909
Okay. I think we're about ready.
I put gas in the tank.

206
00:16:33,993 --> 00:16:35,494
Your future clothes are packed.

207
00:16:35,536 --> 00:16:39,290
Just in case,
fresh batteries for your walkie-talkies.

208
00:16:39,707 --> 00:16:42,251
Oh! What about that floating device?

209
00:16:42,334 --> 00:16:44,295
- Hoverboard.
-All right.

210
00:16:46,380 --> 00:16:49,884
You know, Doc, it's gonna be a hell of
a long walk back to Hill Valley from here.

211
00:16:49,925 --> 00:16:51,218
It's still the safest plan.

212
00:16:51,302 --> 00:16:54,054
After all, we can't risk sending you back
into a populated area

213
00:16:54,096 --> 00:16:56,390
or to a spot that's geographically unknown.

214
00:16:56,432 --> 00:16:59,810
You don't want to crash into some tree
that once existed in the past.

215
00:16:59,894 --> 00:17:02,396
This was all completely open country,

216
00:17:02,438 --> 00:17:05,065
so you'll have plenty of run out space
when you arrive.

217
00:17:05,149 --> 00:17:08,277
Remember, where you're going,
there are no roads.

218
00:17:08,360 --> 00:17:10,101
There's a small cave
over there which will

219
00:17:10,113 --> 00:17:11,989
be a perfect place to
hide the time vehicle.

220
00:17:12,072 --> 00:17:15,826
Well, the new time circuit control tubes
are warmed up.

221
00:17:18,746 --> 00:17:20,581
Time circuits on.

222
00:17:20,664 --> 00:17:23,542
I wrote the letter on September 1st,
so we'll send you back the very next day,

223
00:17:23,584 --> 00:17:27,421
September 2nd. That's a Wednesday.
September 2nd, 1885, 8:00 a.m.

224
00:17:27,463 --> 00:17:30,132
I get shot on Monday the 7th,
so you have five days to locate me.

225
00:17:30,216 --> 00:17:33,552
According to my letter, I'm a blacksmith,
so I probably have a shop somewhere.

226
00:17:34,220 --> 00:17:36,222
All you have to do is
drive the time vehicle

227
00:17:36,263 --> 00:17:39,850
directly toward that screen,
accelerating to 88 miles an hour.

228
00:17:39,934 --> 00:17:42,937
Wait a minute. Doc, if I drive
straight towards the screen,

229
00:17:43,020 --> 00:17:44,563
I'm gonna crash into those Indians.

230
00:17:44,605 --> 00:17:47,983
Marty, you're not thinking
fourth-dimensionally.

231
00:17:48,067 --> 00:17:52,446
You'll instantly be transported to 1885,
and those Indians won't even be there.

232
00:17:53,656 --> 00:17:55,532
- Right.
-Well.

233
00:17:57,243 --> 00:18:01,247
Good luck for both of our sakes.
See you in the future.

234
00:18:02,414 --> 00:18:04,500
- You mean the past.
-Exactly.

235
00:18:11,340 --> 00:18:13,300
Happy trails, Marty!

236
00:18:18,931 --> 00:18:20,349
Ready, Marty?

237
00:18:21,308 --> 00:18:22,518
Ready!

238
00:18:23,143 --> 00:18:25,646
- Set!
-Hi-ho, Silver.

239
00:19:03,058 --> 00:19:04,768
Indians!

240
00:19:43,682 --> 00:19:44,892
The cave!

241
00:20:20,052 --> 00:20:21,303
Charge!

242
00:20:25,516 --> 00:20:26,558
Shit! The cavalry!

243
00:21:17,776 --> 00:21:20,028
Damn, I ripped the fuel line.

244
00:22:04,865 --> 00:22:08,952
Maggie!
Fetch some water! We got a hurt man here.

245
00:22:17,002 --> 00:22:20,881
- Mom! Mom, is that you?
- -There, there now.

246
00:22:20,923 --> 00:22:24,259
You've been asleep
for nearly six hours now.

247
00:22:24,343 --> 00:22:26,637
I had this horrible nightmare.

248
00:22:28,347 --> 00:22:31,683
I dreamed... I dreamed I was in a Western.

249
00:22:33,352 --> 00:22:39,733
I was being chased by all these Indians
and a bear.

250
00:22:39,816 --> 00:22:43,111
Well, you're safe and sound
here now at the McFly farm.

251
00:22:44,029 --> 00:22:45,656
McFly farm?

252
00:22:48,909 --> 00:22:52,412
Well, you're
my... You're my, my...

253
00:22:54,164 --> 00:22:55,290
Who are you?

254
00:22:55,374 --> 00:22:58,001
The name is McFly. Maggie McFly.

255
00:22:58,085 --> 00:23:01,588
McFly. Maggie?

256
00:23:02,005 --> 00:23:05,175
And that's Mrs. McFly,
and don't you be forgetting the Mrs.

257
00:23:05,259 --> 00:23:08,470
- And what might your name be, sir?
-Well, it's...

258
00:23:12,015 --> 00:23:13,350
Eastwood.

259
00:23:15,143 --> 00:23:17,271
Clint Eastwood.

260
00:23:17,771 --> 00:23:19,606
Well, you hit your head, Mr. Eastwood.

261
00:23:19,648 --> 00:23:23,402
Not too serious, but lucky for you,
Seamus found you when he did.

262
00:23:23,443 --> 00:23:25,279
Seamus.

263
00:23:25,320 --> 00:23:26,780
Me husband.

264
00:23:28,448 --> 00:23:32,661
You'll be excusing me, Mr. Eastwood,
while I tend to William.

265
00:23:32,744 --> 00:23:33,745
William.

266
00:23:33,954 --> 00:23:36,582
Oh, that's okay, Will. It's okay.

267
00:23:43,714 --> 00:23:45,716
- That's William?
-Aye.

268
00:23:45,799 --> 00:23:49,386
William Sean McFly, the first of
our family to be born in America.

269
00:23:50,304 --> 00:23:51,722
It's okay, Will.

270
00:23:51,805 --> 00:23:55,392
This here is Mr. Clint
Eastwood here visiting.

271
00:23:55,475 --> 00:23:57,519
He surely likes you, Mr. Eastwood.

272
00:23:58,478 --> 00:23:59,813
Maggie.

273
00:24:02,107 --> 00:24:03,275
I've got supper.

274
00:24:03,317 --> 00:24:05,986
I'm not one to pry
into a man's personal affairs,

275
00:24:06,069 --> 00:24:10,490
but exactly how is it that
you came to be way out here

276
00:24:10,574 --> 00:24:14,911
without a horse, or boots, or a hat?

277
00:24:14,995 --> 00:24:20,417
Well, my car... Horse broke down,
and a bear ate my boots,

278
00:24:20,500 --> 00:24:22,377
and I guess I just forgot my hat.

279
00:24:22,461 --> 00:24:25,255
How could you forget a thing like your hat?

280
00:24:25,339 --> 00:24:27,799
- Would you like some water?
-Yeah.

281
00:24:38,644 --> 00:24:40,979
I'll tell you what I'll do, Mr. Eastwood.

282
00:24:41,021 --> 00:24:43,357
I'll help you find your blacksmith friend.

283
00:24:44,691 --> 00:24:47,861
You can stay the night in the barn,

284
00:24:47,903 --> 00:24:51,073
and tomorrow I'll take you
as far as the railroad tracks.

285
00:24:51,156 --> 00:24:53,450
You can follow them straight on into town.

286
00:24:56,453 --> 00:24:58,121
I'll even give you a hat.

287
00:25:01,458 --> 00:25:02,834
That's great. Thanks.

288
00:25:06,213 --> 00:25:07,756
Ah...

289
00:25:07,881 --> 00:25:08,924
That's my William.

290
00:25:13,261 --> 00:25:14,554
Oh.

291
00:25:15,889 --> 00:25:17,057
Yes.

292
00:25:18,016 --> 00:25:20,602
I think you'll find the barn comfortable.

293
00:25:20,686 --> 00:25:23,605
Never had any complaints about it
from the pigs.

294
00:25:23,689 --> 00:25:25,732
- Mmm.
- Seamus!

295
00:25:25,774 --> 00:25:27,943
- A word with you.
-Aye.

296
00:25:31,655 --> 00:25:34,032
Will you hold him for a minute?

297
00:25:37,744 --> 00:25:40,080
Are you sure you're not after
bringing a curse on this house

298
00:25:40,122 --> 00:25:42,249
taking him in like that?

299
00:25:42,332 --> 00:25:43,834
He's such a strange young man.

300
00:25:43,917 --> 00:25:46,920
Aye. But I've just got a feeling
about him, Maggie,

301
00:25:46,962 --> 00:25:51,174
that looking after him is the right thing
to do. That it's important.

302
00:25:51,258 --> 00:25:52,926
Hey, buddy.

303
00:25:53,009 --> 00:25:55,137
Look how the baby takes to him.

304
00:25:55,220 --> 00:25:58,890
Little Will never takes to strangers.

305
00:25:58,932 --> 00:26:01,893
It's almost as if he's connected to us.

306
00:26:01,935 --> 00:26:02,978
Hey, Will.

307
00:26:03,603 --> 00:26:08,734
So you're my great-grandfather.
The first McFly born in America.

308
00:26:14,448 --> 00:26:16,283
And you peed on me.

309
00:27:07,209 --> 00:27:09,669
- Give us some soap.
-Here you go.

310
00:28:56,818 --> 00:28:59,446
Take a look and see
what just breezed in the door.

311
00:29:02,365 --> 00:29:04,868
Why, I didn't know the circus was in town.

312
00:29:04,951 --> 00:29:08,455
Must have got that
shirt off a dead Chinese.

313
00:29:28,600 --> 00:29:30,185
What will it be, stranger?

314
00:29:32,771 --> 00:29:36,399
I'll have ice water.

315
00:29:36,483 --> 00:29:38,151
Ice water?

316
00:29:39,194 --> 00:29:40,195
Water?

317
00:29:40,278 --> 00:29:43,949
You want water, you better go dunk
your head in the horse trough out there.

318
00:29:45,116 --> 00:29:48,161
In here, we pour whiskey.

319
00:29:59,005 --> 00:30:01,549
- Excuse me.
-For what?

320
00:30:01,633 --> 00:30:04,052
I'm trying to find the blacksmith.

321
00:30:05,095 --> 00:30:06,513
Hey, McFly!

322
00:30:08,515 --> 00:30:11,309
Thought I done told you never to come in...

323
00:30:13,061 --> 00:30:14,854
You ain't Seamus McFly.

324
00:30:16,564 --> 00:30:19,901
You look like him, though,
especially with that dog-ugly hat.

325
00:30:23,238 --> 00:30:25,573
You kin to that hay barber?

326
00:30:25,657 --> 00:30:27,450
What's your name, dude?

327
00:30:27,534 --> 00:30:28,827
Marty...

328
00:30:29,953 --> 00:30:31,246
Eastwood.

329
00:30:32,706 --> 00:30:34,207
Clint Eastwood.

330
00:30:36,084 --> 00:30:40,588
- What kind of stupid name is that?
-I'd say he's the runt of the litter.

331
00:30:40,672 --> 00:30:43,299
Hey, now, boys, would you take a look-see
at these pearly whites?

332
00:30:43,383 --> 00:30:45,802
Hell, I ain't seen teeth look that straight
that weren't store-bought.

333
00:30:45,885 --> 00:30:49,431
Take a gander at them moccasins.
What kind of skins is them?

334
00:30:49,514 --> 00:30:50,598
What's that writing mean?

335
00:30:50,682 --> 00:30:53,727
"Nike"? What is that?
Some sort of Injun talk or something?

336
00:30:56,896 --> 00:31:00,567
Bartender, I'm looking
for that no-good, cheating blacksmith.

337
00:31:00,650 --> 00:31:03,862
- You seen him?
-No, sir, Mr. Tannen. I have not.

338
00:31:05,405 --> 00:31:06,698
Tannen.

339
00:31:07,574 --> 00:31:08,950
You're "Mad Dog" Tannen.

340
00:31:15,331 --> 00:31:17,125
"Mad Dog"?

341
00:31:17,208 --> 00:31:18,543
I hate that name.

342
00:31:19,544 --> 00:31:22,172
I hate it, you hear?

343
00:31:22,255 --> 00:31:25,133
Nobody calls me "Mad Dog"!

344
00:31:25,216 --> 00:31:29,137
Especially not some duded-up,
egg-sucking gutter trash.

345
00:31:31,306 --> 00:31:33,183
Dance!

346
00:31:33,266 --> 00:31:34,350
Come on!

347
00:31:36,603 --> 00:31:39,522
Come on, runt!
You can dance better than that!

348
00:31:49,783 --> 00:31:50,825
Shit.

349
00:31:52,035 --> 00:31:53,203
Whoo!

350
00:32:12,680 --> 00:32:14,307
You better run, squirrel.

351
00:32:14,349 --> 00:32:15,725
Get him!

352
00:32:27,612 --> 00:32:28,822
Whoa!

353
00:33:19,414 --> 00:33:23,877
We got ourselves a new courthouse.
High time we had a hanging!

354
00:33:43,938 --> 00:33:45,648
Look at him swing.

355
00:33:49,110 --> 00:33:52,405
Yeah, haven't had
a hanging in a long time!

356
00:33:55,617 --> 00:33:58,953
It'll shoot the fleas off a dog's back
at 500 yards, Tannen,

357
00:33:59,037 --> 00:34:01,039
and it's pointed straight at your head!

358
00:34:11,549 --> 00:34:14,552
- You owe me money, blacksmith.
-How do you figure?

359
00:34:14,594 --> 00:34:16,262
My horse threw a shoe.

360
00:34:16,304 --> 00:34:17,847
And seeing as you was the one
that done the shoeing,

361
00:34:17,931 --> 00:34:19,307
I say that makes you responsible.

362
00:34:19,390 --> 00:34:23,394
Well, since you never paid me for the job,
I say that makes us even.

363
00:34:23,436 --> 00:34:27,315
Wrong! See I was on my horse when it
threw the shoe, and I got throwed off!

364
00:34:27,398 --> 00:34:32,070
And that caused me to bust a perfectly
good bottle of fine Kentucky red eye.

365
00:34:32,111 --> 00:34:35,949
So the way I figure it, blacksmith,
you owe me $5 for the whiskey

366
00:34:36,032 --> 00:34:38,243
and $75 for the horse!

367
00:34:39,118 --> 00:34:40,245
That's the $80.

368
00:34:40,286 --> 00:34:44,749
Look, if your horse threw a shoe,
bring him back, and I'll reshoe him.

369
00:34:44,791 --> 00:34:46,459
I done shot that horse!

370
00:34:46,501 --> 00:34:48,711
Well, that's your problem, Tannen.

371
00:34:48,795 --> 00:34:51,839
Wrong. That's yours.

372
00:34:51,923 --> 00:34:55,635
So from now on, you better be looking
behind you when you walk.

373
00:34:55,677 --> 00:34:58,304
Because one day you're gonna get
a bullet in your back.

374
00:35:08,314 --> 00:35:09,315
Doc!

375
00:35:09,357 --> 00:35:14,487
Marty, I gave you explicit instructions
not to come here

376
00:35:14,570 --> 00:35:16,781
but to go directly back to 1985.

377
00:35:16,823 --> 00:35:19,492
I know, Doc, but I had to come.

378
00:35:20,326 --> 00:35:22,745
But it's good to see you, Marty.

379
00:35:27,000 --> 00:35:29,002
Marty, you're gonna have to do something
about those clothes.

380
00:35:29,043 --> 00:35:32,046
You walk around town dressed like that,
you're liable to get shot.

381
00:35:32,130 --> 00:35:33,131
Or hanged.

382
00:35:33,172 --> 00:35:36,342
What idiot dressed you in that outfit?

383
00:35:36,384 --> 00:35:37,677
You did.

384
00:35:40,513 --> 00:35:42,765
"Shot in the back
by Buford Tannen

385
00:35:43,141 --> 00:35:45,101
"over a matter of $80,

386
00:35:45,268 --> 00:35:47,437
"September 7"?

387
00:35:47,520 --> 00:35:49,522
That's this Monday!

388
00:35:49,605 --> 00:35:52,108
Now I wish I'd paid him off.

389
00:35:52,191 --> 00:35:56,362
And who's this beloved Clara?
I don't know anyone named Clara.

390
00:35:56,404 --> 00:35:59,198
I don't know, Doc.

391
00:35:59,282 --> 00:36:01,492
I thought maybe
she was a girlfriend of yours.

392
00:36:01,534 --> 00:36:06,831
Marty, my involvement in such
a social relationship here in 1885

393
00:36:06,873 --> 00:36:10,793
could result in a disruption
of the space-time continuum.

394
00:36:10,877 --> 00:36:14,922
As a scientist, I can never take that risk.

395
00:36:16,549 --> 00:36:19,093
Certainly not after what
we've already been through.

396
00:36:19,177 --> 00:36:20,303
Emmett!

397
00:36:20,386 --> 00:36:22,764
- Hello, Emmett.
- Hubert.

398
00:36:23,306 --> 00:36:26,809
- It's the mayor.
-Excuse me, Emmett.

399
00:36:26,893 --> 00:36:29,562
Do you remember last week
at the town meeting when you volunteered

400
00:36:29,645 --> 00:36:32,106
to meet the new schoolteacher
at the station when she came in?

401
00:36:32,190 --> 00:36:33,191
Oh, yes, quite so.

402
00:36:33,232 --> 00:36:35,735
Well, we just got word
she's coming in tomorrow.

403
00:36:35,777 --> 00:36:37,737
Here are the details for you.

404
00:36:37,820 --> 00:36:41,282
- Thanks for all your help.
-Anytime, Hubert.

405
00:36:41,407 --> 00:36:45,411
Oh! Her name's Miss Clayton. Clara Clayton.

406
00:36:53,920 --> 00:36:58,091
Well, Doc, now we know who Clara is.

407
00:36:59,842 --> 00:37:02,095
Marty, it's impossible.

408
00:37:02,136 --> 00:37:05,431
The idea that I could fall in love
at first sight is romantic nonsense.

409
00:37:06,599 --> 00:37:08,851
There's no scientific rationale
for that concept.

410
00:37:08,935 --> 00:37:10,937
Come on, Doc. It's not science.

411
00:37:11,020 --> 00:37:13,564
You meet the right girl,
it just hits you. It's like lightning.

412
00:37:13,606 --> 00:37:15,233
Marty, please don't say that.

413
00:37:15,274 --> 00:37:17,860
That's the way it was for me and Jennifer.

414
00:37:17,944 --> 00:37:20,947
I mean,
we couldn't keep our eyes off each other.

415
00:37:20,988 --> 00:37:23,074
God, Jennifer, damn.
I hope she's all right, Doc.

416
00:37:23,116 --> 00:37:25,451
I can't believe
we just left her there on the porch.

417
00:37:25,535 --> 00:37:27,537
Don't worry, Marty. She'll be fine.

418
00:37:27,620 --> 00:37:31,416
When you burned the almanac in 1955,
the normal timeline was restored.

419
00:37:31,457 --> 00:37:33,251
That means once we're back in 1985,

420
00:37:33,292 --> 00:37:35,294
you just have to go over to her house
to wake her up.

421
00:37:37,171 --> 00:37:40,633
Oh, Marty, turn that valve over there
all the way to the right.

422
00:37:40,675 --> 00:37:42,593
Yeah, pull it all the way around.

423
00:37:42,635 --> 00:37:44,137
Okay. Let's go!

424
00:37:58,317 --> 00:38:01,821
- Iced tea?
-No, thanks.

425
00:38:01,904 --> 00:38:03,823
It's a refrigerator.

426
00:38:03,865 --> 00:38:07,577
Well, I guess Miss Clayton
will have to find other transportation.

427
00:38:07,660 --> 00:38:09,121
If I never meet the
woman, there's no

428
00:38:09,133 --> 00:38:10,955
possibility of a romantic
infatuation, right?

429
00:38:10,997 --> 00:38:12,874
- You're the doc, Doc.
-All right.

430
00:38:12,957 --> 00:38:15,501
We'll get the DeLorean
and get ourselves back to the future.

431
00:38:15,585 --> 00:38:18,171
Oh, listen, Doc, I tore a hole in
the gas tank when I was landing,

432
00:38:18,254 --> 00:38:20,840
so we're gonna have to patch it up
and get some gas.

433
00:38:20,923 --> 00:38:23,217
You mean we're out of gas?

434
00:38:23,301 --> 00:38:26,012
Yeah, it's no big deal.
We've got Mr. Fusion, right?

435
00:38:26,095 --> 00:38:29,974
Mr. Fusion powers the time circuits
and the Flux Capacitor,

436
00:38:30,016 --> 00:38:32,977
but the internal combustion engine
runs on ordinary gasoline.

437
00:38:33,019 --> 00:38:34,770
It always has.

438
00:38:34,854 --> 00:38:36,856
There's not gonna be
a gas station around here

439
00:38:36,898 --> 00:38:39,525
until sometime in the next century.

440
00:38:39,609 --> 00:38:44,530
Without gasoline, we can't get
the DeLorean up to 88 miles per hour.

441
00:38:47,074 --> 00:38:48,493
So what do we do?

442
00:38:58,961 --> 00:39:02,215
- Twenty-four!
-It's no use, Marty!

443
00:39:02,256 --> 00:39:07,220
Even the fastest horse in the world
won't run more than 35, 40 miles an hour!

444
00:39:17,897 --> 00:39:21,067
Bartender said
that's the strongest stuff they got.

445
00:39:21,150 --> 00:39:22,735
Try it, Marty.

446
00:39:33,955 --> 00:39:35,748
Give it more gas!

447
00:39:45,049 --> 00:39:46,259
Damn!

448
00:39:48,261 --> 00:39:52,848
It blew the fuel injection manifold.
Strong stuff, all right.

449
00:39:52,932 --> 00:39:55,893
It will take me a month to rebuild it.

450
00:39:55,935 --> 00:39:57,311
A month?

451
00:39:57,645 --> 00:39:59,438
Doc, you're gonna get shot on Monday!

452
00:39:59,522 --> 00:40:03,109
I know! I know! I know! I wish...

453
00:40:03,150 --> 00:40:07,905
Wait. I've got it!
We can simply roll it down a steep hill!

454
00:40:07,947 --> 00:40:10,950
Oh! We'd never find
a smooth enough surface. Unless...

455
00:40:11,033 --> 00:40:12,994
Of course! Ice!

456
00:40:13,077 --> 00:40:15,288
We'll wait until winter
when the lake freezes over.

457
00:40:15,371 --> 00:40:18,666
Winter? Doc, what are you talking about?
Monday! It's three days away!

458
00:40:18,749 --> 00:40:23,045
All right, all right, all right. Just
let's think this thing through logically.

459
00:40:23,129 --> 00:40:26,841
We know it won't run under its own power.
We know we can't pull it.

460
00:40:26,924 --> 00:40:30,428
But if we could figure out a way

461
00:40:30,469 --> 00:40:33,639
to push it up to 88 miles an hour.

462
00:40:33,723 --> 00:40:35,099
Huh?

463
00:40:43,274 --> 00:40:44,358
That's it.

464
00:40:44,442 --> 00:40:48,321
How fast can she go?
Why, I've had her up to 55 myself.

465
00:40:49,488 --> 00:40:52,908
I heard that Fearless Frank Fargo
got one of these up to near 70

466
00:40:52,992 --> 00:40:54,827
out past Verde Junction.

467
00:40:54,869 --> 00:40:57,538
Do you think it's
possible to get it up to 90?

468
00:40:57,622 --> 00:41:01,792
Ninety? Tarnation, son,
who'd ever need to be in such a hurry?

469
00:41:01,834 --> 00:41:04,086
It's just a little bet he
and I have, that's all.

470
00:41:04,170 --> 00:41:06,672
Theoretically speaking, could it be done?

471
00:41:06,756 --> 00:41:10,509
Well, I suppose, if you had a straight
stretch of track with a level grade,

472
00:41:10,593 --> 00:41:14,930
and you weren't hauling no cars behind you,
and if you could get the fire hot enough.

473
00:41:15,014 --> 00:41:19,018
And I'm talking about hotter than
the blazes of hell and damnation itself.

474
00:41:19,060 --> 00:41:21,312
Then yes, sir, it might be possible
to get her up that fast.

475
00:41:21,354 --> 00:41:23,481
Tell me, when does the next train
come through here?

476
00:41:23,522 --> 00:41:24,982
Monday morning at 8:00.

477
00:41:25,024 --> 00:41:29,195
Here. This spur that runs off the main line
three miles out to Clayton Ravine.

478
00:41:29,278 --> 00:41:33,240
It's a long stretch of level track
that will still exist in 1985.

479
00:41:33,324 --> 00:41:36,827
This is where we'll push the DeLorean
with the locomotive.

480
00:41:36,869 --> 00:41:40,414
Funny. This map calls Clayton Ravine
Shonash Ravine.

481
00:41:40,498 --> 00:41:43,626
That must be the old Indian name for it.
It's perfect.

482
00:41:43,709 --> 00:41:46,629
A nice long run that goes
clear across the bridge over the ravine,

483
00:41:46,712 --> 00:41:49,048
you know, over near that
Hilldale housing development.

484
00:41:49,131 --> 00:41:53,719
Right, Doc, but according to this map,
there is no bridge.

485
00:41:54,095 --> 00:41:57,640
Well, Doc, we can scratch that idea.

486
00:41:57,723 --> 00:42:00,226
I mean, we can't wait a year and a half
for this thing to get finished.

487
00:42:00,267 --> 00:42:01,727
Marty, it's perfect.

488
00:42:01,769 --> 00:42:03,896
You're just not thinking
fourth-dimensionally.

489
00:42:03,979 --> 00:42:05,731
Right. Right. I have a
real problem with that.

490
00:42:05,773 --> 00:42:09,694
Don't you see? The
bridge will exist in 1985.

491
00:42:09,735 --> 00:42:11,612
It's safe and still in use.

492
00:42:11,696 --> 00:42:14,532
Therefore, as long as we get the DeLorean
up to 88 miles an hour

493
00:42:14,573 --> 00:42:16,283
before we hit the edge of the ravine,

494
00:42:16,367 --> 00:42:21,080
we'll instantaneously arrive at a point
in time where the bridge is completed.

495
00:42:21,122 --> 00:42:26,711
We'll have track under us
and coast safely across the ravine.

496
00:42:26,752 --> 00:42:30,005
- What about the locomotive?
-It will be a spectacular wreck.

497
00:42:30,089 --> 00:42:31,966
Too bad no one will be around to see it.

498
00:42:33,801 --> 00:42:35,678
Help me! Help!

499
00:42:35,761 --> 00:42:37,138
Great Scott!

500
00:43:19,638 --> 00:43:20,723
Hurry!

501
00:43:22,850 --> 00:43:24,143
Jump!

502
00:43:34,445 --> 00:43:35,446
Whoa.

503
00:43:36,280 --> 00:43:37,448
Whoa.

504
00:43:37,823 --> 00:43:38,866
Oh...

505
00:43:38,949 --> 00:43:41,660
Thank you, sir. You saved my...

506
00:43:43,913 --> 00:43:44,955
...life.

507
00:43:49,335 --> 00:43:51,796
Emmett Brown at your service, Miss...

508
00:43:55,216 --> 00:43:56,550
Clayton.

509
00:43:58,177 --> 00:43:59,345
Clara Clayton.

510
00:44:00,679 --> 00:44:01,680
Clara!

511
00:44:05,518 --> 00:44:07,228
What a beautiful name.

512
00:44:24,703 --> 00:44:27,373
May I help you inside with these?

513
00:44:27,456 --> 00:44:30,209
Oh, no, that won't be necessary.
I can take care of it.

514
00:44:30,251 --> 00:44:34,588
- You've done more than enough already.
-But it's really no trouble.

515
00:44:34,672 --> 00:44:37,049
Doc, she says it's fine,
and we got to get going.

516
00:44:37,132 --> 00:44:40,886
Ma'am, good luck with your school teaching
and everything.

517
00:44:40,970 --> 00:44:45,891
Clara, I'll straighten everything out
with Mr. Statler for the buckboard rental.

518
00:44:45,933 --> 00:44:47,268
Don't worry about that.

519
00:44:47,351 --> 00:44:49,395
I feel somewhat responsible
for what happened.

520
00:44:49,478 --> 00:44:50,479
Oh.

521
00:44:51,397 --> 00:44:55,150
That would be very gentlemanly of you,
Mr. Brown. Emmett.

522
00:44:58,028 --> 00:45:01,949
You know, I'm almost glad
that snake spooked those horses.

523
00:45:02,032 --> 00:45:04,952
Otherwise, we might never have met.

524
00:45:05,035 --> 00:45:06,537
I suppose it was destiny.

525
00:45:10,082 --> 00:45:12,251
Well, thank you for everything.

526
00:45:12,668 --> 00:45:14,545
You're quite welcome.

527
00:45:16,881 --> 00:45:19,550
I will see you again, won't I?

528
00:45:19,592 --> 00:45:22,428
Of course. You'll see lots of me. I'm sure.
I have a shop in town.

529
00:45:22,469 --> 00:45:25,347
I'm the local scientist,
blacksmith.

530
00:45:26,015 --> 00:45:30,603
Science? What sort of science?
Astronomy? Chemistry?

531
00:45:31,061 --> 00:45:33,522
Actually, I'm a student of all sciences.

532
00:45:33,606 --> 00:45:36,650
Hey, Doc, we got to get going.

533
00:45:36,734 --> 00:45:39,737
Oh, yes. Well, excuse us, Clara.

534
00:45:39,778 --> 00:45:41,614
We have to get going.

535
00:45:46,201 --> 00:45:47,286
Toodle-oo.

536
00:45:55,669 --> 00:45:57,630
What do you mean,
you're gonna be seeing lots of her, Doc?

537
00:45:57,713 --> 00:46:00,883
Well, I might see her
again just in passing.

538
00:46:00,966 --> 00:46:03,093
Come on, Doc. Did you see the way
she was looking at you?

539
00:46:05,054 --> 00:46:08,140
She did have quite a scare, right?

540
00:46:08,223 --> 00:46:11,685
After all, Miss Clayton almost ended up
at the bottom of Clayton Ravine.

541
00:46:11,769 --> 00:46:12,770
Clayton Ravine.

542
00:46:12,811 --> 00:46:17,983
Holy shit. Hey, Doc, Clayton Ravine
was named after a teacher.

543
00:46:18,025 --> 00:46:22,947
- They say she fell in there 100 years ago.
-100 years ago! That's this year!

544
00:46:22,988 --> 00:46:24,239
Every kid in school knows that story,

545
00:46:24,323 --> 00:46:27,368
'cause we all have teachers
we'd like to see fall into the ravine.

546
00:46:27,451 --> 00:46:28,911
Great Scott!

547
00:46:30,287 --> 00:46:33,499
Then she was supposed to go over
in that wagon.

548
00:46:34,667 --> 00:46:37,544
Now I may have seriously altered history.

549
00:46:38,671 --> 00:46:41,715
Look, Doc, what's the worst
that can happen, huh?

550
00:46:41,799 --> 00:46:44,176
So they don't name the ravine after her.

551
00:46:44,259 --> 00:46:46,637
Let's just get the DeLorean ready
and get the hell out of here.

552
00:46:46,679 --> 00:46:50,140
I wish I'd never invented
that infernal time machine.

553
00:46:51,475 --> 00:46:54,228
It's caused nothing but disaster.

554
00:46:57,815 --> 00:46:59,108
Doc, Doc, this is Marty.

555
00:46:59,191 --> 00:47:00,234
Do you read me? Over.

556
00:47:00,317 --> 00:47:01,360
Check, Marty.

557
00:47:01,443 --> 00:47:03,862
Great, Doc. These things still work.

558
00:47:03,904 --> 00:47:08,867
All right, Marty. Once more,
let's go over the entire plan and layout.

559
00:47:08,951 --> 00:47:10,995
I apologize for the crudity of this model,
but I just...

560
00:47:11,036 --> 00:47:14,039
Yeah, I know, Doc.
It's not to scale. It's okay, Doc.

561
00:47:14,123 --> 00:47:17,626
All right. Tomorrow night, Sunday,

562
00:47:17,710 --> 00:47:20,546
we'll load the DeLorean
onto the tracks here, on the spur

563
00:47:20,629 --> 00:47:22,965
right by the old abandoned silver mine.

564
00:47:23,048 --> 00:47:25,884
The switch track is where
the spur runs off the main line

565
00:47:25,926 --> 00:47:29,430
three miles out to Clayton...
Shonash Ravine.

566
00:47:29,513 --> 00:47:32,349
The train leaves the station
at 8:00 Monday morning.

567
00:47:32,391 --> 00:47:34,977
We'll stop it here,
uncouple the cars from the tender,

568
00:47:35,060 --> 00:47:37,229
throw the switch track,
and then we'll hijack...

569
00:47:37,312 --> 00:47:41,275
Borrow the locomotive and use it
to push the time machine.

570
00:47:41,358 --> 00:47:44,069
According to my calculations,
we'll reach 88 miles per hour

571
00:47:44,111 --> 00:47:46,155
just before we hit the edge of the ravine,

572
00:47:46,238 --> 00:47:49,908
at which point we'll be instantaneously
transported back to 1985

573
00:47:49,950 --> 00:47:52,411
and coast safely
across the completed bridge.

574
00:47:52,453 --> 00:47:55,247
What does this mean? "Point of no return."

575
00:47:55,289 --> 00:47:58,751
That's our fail-safe point. Up until there,
we have still have enough time

576
00:47:58,792 --> 00:48:01,420
to stop the locomotive
before it plunges into the ravine.

577
00:48:01,462 --> 00:48:03,881
But once we pass this windmill,
it's the future or bust.

578
00:48:06,884 --> 00:48:10,596
Here you go, Marty.
Connect that to the positive terminal.

579
00:48:11,597 --> 00:48:13,932
- All right, Marty, you all set?
-Yeah. Yeah. Go!

580
00:48:14,391 --> 00:48:17,102
Train pulling out of the station!

581
00:48:17,144 --> 00:48:19,313
Coming up to the switch track!

582
00:48:19,396 --> 00:48:21,982
Stop at the switch track!

583
00:48:22,066 --> 00:48:24,318
Throw the switch!

584
00:48:24,401 --> 00:48:26,820
Pull up to the DeLorean!

585
00:48:26,904 --> 00:48:31,075
Pushing the DeLorean up
to 88 miles per hour!

586
00:48:37,456 --> 00:48:38,540
It couldn't be simpler.

587
00:48:40,375 --> 00:48:41,376
Hello?

588
00:48:45,923 --> 00:48:47,966
Emmett?

589
00:48:48,008 --> 00:48:49,635
It's Clara.

590
00:48:49,676 --> 00:48:51,762
Quick, cover the DeLorean!

591
00:48:59,061 --> 00:49:01,355
- Hello.
-Why, hello.

592
00:49:01,438 --> 00:49:03,565
This is quite a surprise.

593
00:49:05,109 --> 00:49:07,277
Well, I hope I'm not disturbing anything.

594
00:49:07,319 --> 00:49:10,864
Oh, no, no, we were just doing
a little model railroading.

595
00:49:11,448 --> 00:49:12,533
Oh.

596
00:49:13,992 --> 00:49:17,037
Emmett, when my bags
were thrown from the wagon,

597
00:49:17,121 --> 00:49:18,997
my telescope was damaged.

598
00:49:19,081 --> 00:49:22,668
And since you mentioned
an interest in science,

599
00:49:22,709 --> 00:49:26,046
I thought you might be able
to repair it for me.

600
00:49:26,130 --> 00:49:28,132
I would pay you, of course.

601
00:49:28,173 --> 00:49:32,511
Oh, no, no, no.
I wouldn't think of charging you for this.

602
00:49:32,553 --> 00:49:34,721
Well, let's have a look at it.

603
00:49:34,805 --> 00:49:37,099
I think a lens
may be out of alignment,

604
00:49:37,182 --> 00:49:43,856
because if you move it this way,
the image turns fuzzy. See?

605
00:49:43,897 --> 00:49:48,986
But if you turn it the other way then...

606
00:49:49,945 --> 00:49:51,738
Everything becomes...

607
00:49:54,700 --> 00:49:56,034
...clear.

608
00:50:01,165 --> 00:50:03,959
I could repair it right away
and have it for you tonight.

609
00:50:04,042 --> 00:50:06,753
Oh, tonight is the town festival.

610
00:50:06,837 --> 00:50:09,381
I wouldn't dream of having
you work on my telescope

611
00:50:09,464 --> 00:50:11,258
during such an important occasion.

612
00:50:11,341 --> 00:50:14,469
You are planning on attending, aren't you?

613
00:50:15,721 --> 00:50:20,058
- Well, actually, ma'am, I don't think...
-Yes, of course, the festival.

614
00:50:20,142 --> 00:50:25,731
Well, in that case, I'll see you
this evening at the festival, Emmett.

615
00:50:25,772 --> 00:50:27,733
- Mr. Eastwood.
-Ma'am.

616
00:50:30,819 --> 00:50:33,238
Thank you for taking care of my telescope.

617
00:50:33,322 --> 00:50:35,240
You're quite welcome.

618
00:50:41,205 --> 00:50:42,623
It's a nice telescope.

619
00:50:42,706 --> 00:50:45,375
Ladies and gentlemen,

620
00:50:45,417 --> 00:50:49,838
as mayor of Hill Valley,
it gives me great pleasure

621
00:50:49,922 --> 00:50:53,091
to dedicate this clock
to the people of Hill County!

622
00:50:54,259 --> 00:50:57,930
May it stand for all time!

623
00:50:58,013 --> 00:50:59,431
Tell me when, gentlemen.

624
00:51:00,599 --> 00:51:04,436
Three! Two! One!

625
00:51:05,229 --> 00:51:06,563
Now!

626
00:51:11,985 --> 00:51:14,446
Let the festivities begin!

627
00:51:22,120 --> 00:51:25,624
You know, Marty, in a way, it's fitting
that you and I are here to witness this.

628
00:51:25,666 --> 00:51:28,335
It's too bad I didn't bring my camera.

629
00:51:35,050 --> 00:51:36,176
Ready, gentlemen?

630
00:51:37,594 --> 00:51:40,973
The only problem is
we'll never be able to show it to anybody.

631
00:51:41,056 --> 00:51:42,266
Smile, Doc.

632
00:51:44,726 --> 00:51:45,978
Yee-ha!

633
00:52:06,999 --> 00:52:09,334
What great music!

634
00:52:09,418 --> 00:52:12,170
Yeah, it's got a beat,
and you can dance to it.

635
00:52:12,212 --> 00:52:15,257
Step right up gentlemen and test
your mettle with the latest products

636
00:52:15,340 --> 00:52:19,386
from Colonel Samuel Colt's Patent
Firearms Manufacturing Company

637
00:52:19,469 --> 00:52:21,096
of Hartford, Connecticut.

638
00:52:21,179 --> 00:52:23,015
Now, take this model, for example.

639
00:52:24,182 --> 00:52:27,853
The new, improved and refined
Colt Peacemaker

640
00:52:27,894 --> 00:52:33,108
selling to you tonight
for the low, low price of $12.

641
00:52:49,249 --> 00:52:51,209
- Good evening.
-Evening.

642
00:52:52,461 --> 00:52:54,880
You look very nice.

643
00:52:54,963 --> 00:52:56,423
Thank you.

644
00:53:05,307 --> 00:53:06,933
Would you like...

645
00:53:08,810 --> 00:53:11,313
- Would you care to...
-I'd love to.

646
00:53:29,706 --> 00:53:31,666
Young man, how about you?
You want to give it a try?

647
00:53:31,750 --> 00:53:34,920
No, no. No, thanks. Hey, Doc, this...

648
00:53:42,803 --> 00:53:44,054
Son!

649
00:53:44,846 --> 00:53:47,432
- Sonny boy!
-The Doc can dance?

650
00:53:50,060 --> 00:53:53,939
Son. Son. Son!

651
00:53:53,980 --> 00:53:58,443
Hey, I just told you that even a baby
could handle this weapon.

652
00:53:58,485 --> 00:54:01,613
Surely you're not afraid to try something
that a baby could do.

653
00:54:01,655 --> 00:54:02,948
Hey, I'm not afraid of nothing.

654
00:54:02,989 --> 00:54:05,992
Come on, then.
Let's just step up here like a man.

655
00:54:06,076 --> 00:54:10,497
Now, then what you do
is you just ease that hammer back there

656
00:54:10,580 --> 00:54:12,290
and squeeze off a round.

657
00:54:12,374 --> 00:54:13,959
No, no, no!

658
00:54:14,042 --> 00:54:16,837
Right on out there and be real smooth.

659
00:54:16,920 --> 00:54:18,964
That's the way you do it.

660
00:54:22,467 --> 00:54:25,637
- Listen, can I try that again?
-Yeah, go ahead.

661
00:54:37,774 --> 00:54:42,195
Hey, just tell me one thing.
Where did you learn to shoot like that?

662
00:54:42,279 --> 00:54:43,613
7-Eleven.

663
00:54:48,493 --> 00:54:51,663
Buford, you sure that blacksmith
is gonna be at this here shindig?

664
00:54:51,746 --> 00:54:54,583
Sure he's here. Everybody's here tonight.

665
00:54:57,169 --> 00:54:59,004
You gentlemen will have
to check your firearms

666
00:54:59,087 --> 00:55:01,423
if you want to join in on the festivities.

667
00:55:02,716 --> 00:55:04,259
Who's gonna make us, tenderfoot? You?

668
00:55:04,342 --> 00:55:05,844
I am.

669
00:55:08,847 --> 00:55:11,600
Marshal Strickland.
I didn't know you was back in town.

670
00:55:11,683 --> 00:55:15,604
If you can't read the sign, Tannen,
I presume you can read this.

671
00:55:16,021 --> 00:55:18,815
Pretty tough hombre when you're pointing
a scatter gun at a man's back.

672
00:55:18,857 --> 00:55:22,027
Just like you, Tannen,
I take every advantage I can get.

673
00:55:22,068 --> 00:55:24,738
Now you gonna check your iron?

674
00:55:25,405 --> 00:55:29,701
I was just joking with your deputy.
Of course, I'm gonna check my iron.

675
00:55:29,743 --> 00:55:32,537
- We all were. Weren't we, boys?
- Yeah, right.

676
00:55:34,206 --> 00:55:35,707
Tannen.

677
00:55:36,833 --> 00:55:38,627
Your knife, too.

678
00:55:45,550 --> 00:55:48,720
Smile, Marshal. After all, this is a party.

679
00:55:48,762 --> 00:55:54,017
Only party I'll be smiling at is the
one that sees you at the end of a rope.

680
00:55:56,895 --> 00:55:58,396
Have fun!

681
00:56:02,067 --> 00:56:03,401
See, that's how you handle them, Son.

682
00:56:03,443 --> 00:56:06,905
Never give them an inch
and maintain discipline at all times.

683
00:56:06,988 --> 00:56:09,950
Remember that word, discipline.

684
00:56:10,033 --> 00:56:11,535
I will, Pa.

685
00:56:12,327 --> 00:56:14,746
Swing that partner
With a right big swing

686
00:56:14,829 --> 00:56:17,082
Over to the side
It's the same old thing

687
00:56:17,415 --> 00:56:18,500
Thank you very much.

688
00:56:18,583 --> 00:56:22,921
Why, Mr. Eastwood, nice to see you.

689
00:56:23,004 --> 00:56:27,425
I see you got yourself some
respectable clothes, lad, and a fine hat.

690
00:56:27,509 --> 00:56:30,887
Yeah, well, a couple people didn't like
the way the other one looked on me.

691
00:56:30,929 --> 00:56:32,597
Sure, and that one suits you, Mr. Eastwood.

692
00:56:32,681 --> 00:56:34,599
- It's very becoming.
-Oh, thanks.

693
00:56:35,767 --> 00:56:38,645
Hey, "Frisbie." Far out.

694
00:56:41,439 --> 00:56:42,774
What was the meaning of that?

695
00:56:42,857 --> 00:56:44,484
- It was right in front of him.
-Aye.

696
00:56:44,568 --> 00:56:46,778
Swing that partner halfway round

697
00:56:46,820 --> 00:56:49,114
Sashay back to the head of the set

698
00:56:49,155 --> 00:56:52,158
All the way up to the head of the set

699
00:56:52,242 --> 00:56:54,953
Now, bow to the partner
You're through

700
00:56:59,207 --> 00:57:00,792
- Hey, that's mine!
-Not anymore.

701
00:57:00,875 --> 00:57:03,712
- Give me that.
-There he is, Buford.

702
00:57:05,046 --> 00:57:06,590
- Where?
-There.

703
00:57:06,631 --> 00:57:09,134
Dancing with that piece of calico.

704
00:57:09,217 --> 00:57:11,428
What are you gonna do, boss?

705
00:57:13,305 --> 00:57:18,643
I figure if I bury this muzzle deep enough
in his back, nobody will hear the shot.

706
00:57:18,685 --> 00:57:21,104
Careful, Buford.
You ain't got but one bullet with that.

707
00:57:21,146 --> 00:57:22,981
I only need one.

708
00:57:34,701 --> 00:57:36,620
I told you to watch your back, smithy.

709
00:57:36,661 --> 00:57:38,913
Tannen, you're early.

710
00:57:38,997 --> 00:57:41,374
It's a Derringer, smithy.
Small but effective.

711
00:57:41,458 --> 00:57:44,169
The last time I used it,
fellow took two whole days to die.

712
00:57:44,210 --> 00:57:45,962
Bled to death inside.
It was real, real painful.

713
00:57:47,130 --> 00:57:50,800
That means you'll be dead
by about supper time Monday.

714
00:57:50,842 --> 00:57:54,220
Excuse me. I don't know who you think
you are, but we're dancing.

715
00:57:54,304 --> 00:57:56,473
Well, look at what we have here.

716
00:57:56,514 --> 00:57:59,184
Ain't you gonna introduce me to the lady?
I'd like a dance.

717
00:57:59,267 --> 00:58:03,021
I wouldn't give you the pleasure.
You'll just have to go ahead and shoot.

718
00:58:03,104 --> 00:58:05,357
- All right.
-No, no. Emmett, I'll dance with him.

719
00:58:05,440 --> 00:58:09,319
Boys, keep the blacksmith company
while I get acquainted with the filly!

720
00:58:15,450 --> 00:58:18,870
I don't dance very well
when my partner has a gun in his hand.

721
00:58:18,953 --> 00:58:21,498
You'll learn. You'll learn.

722
00:58:21,539 --> 00:58:24,834
You know, smithy, maybe I'll just take
my $80 worth out of her!

723
00:58:24,876 --> 00:58:26,127
Tannen, leave her alone!

724
00:58:27,587 --> 00:58:29,297
Whoo!

725
00:58:29,839 --> 00:58:33,301
Yeah, I bet there's something you can do
that's worth $80.

726
00:58:34,594 --> 00:58:37,138
I believe you've underestimated me, mister.

727
00:58:37,222 --> 00:58:38,640
Have I?

728
00:58:42,602 --> 00:58:43,853
Ow!

729
00:58:46,106 --> 00:58:49,109
Stop it! Damn you, Tannen!

730
00:58:49,192 --> 00:58:51,611
No, I damn you!

731
00:58:53,113 --> 00:58:55,782
I damn you to hell!

732
00:59:02,414 --> 00:59:03,581
You.

733
00:59:03,665 --> 00:59:05,250
Hey, lighten up, jerk!

734
00:59:09,379 --> 00:59:11,381
Mighty strong words, runt!

735
00:59:11,423 --> 00:59:15,468
You man enough to back them up
with more than just a pie plate?

736
00:59:17,846 --> 00:59:20,974
Look, just leave my friends alone.

737
00:59:21,057 --> 00:59:23,518
What's wrong, dude? You yellow?

738
00:59:31,109 --> 00:59:33,987
That's what I thought. A yellow belly.

739
00:59:40,076 --> 00:59:42,954
Nobody calls me yellow.

740
00:59:43,621 --> 00:59:46,916
Then let's finish it right now.

741
00:59:46,958 --> 00:59:49,753
Not now, Buford. Marshal's got our guns.

742
00:59:49,794 --> 00:59:51,963
Like I said, we'll finish this tomorrow!

743
00:59:52,005 --> 00:59:55,300
Tomorrow we're robbing the Pine City stage.

744
00:59:55,383 --> 00:59:57,886
What about Monday?
We doing anything Monday?

745
00:59:57,969 --> 00:59:59,929
No, Monday would be fine.
You can kill him on Monday.

746
00:59:59,971 --> 01:00:03,933
I'll be back this way on Monday.
We'll settle this then.

747
01:00:03,975 --> 01:00:08,146
Right there out in the street
in front of the Palace Saloon.

748
01:00:09,731 --> 01:00:11,816
Yeah, right. When?

749
01:00:11,900 --> 01:00:13,818
- High noon?
-Noon?

750
01:00:14,319 --> 01:00:18,072
I do my killing before breakfast. 7:00!

751
01:00:20,658 --> 01:00:25,330
8:00. I do my killing after breakfast.

752
01:00:25,413 --> 01:00:26,831
Marty!

753
01:00:31,544 --> 01:00:32,587
All right, now. Break it up.

754
01:00:32,670 --> 01:00:36,508
What's all this about?
You causing trouble here, Tannen?

755
01:00:36,549 --> 01:00:38,301
No trouble, Marshal.

756
01:00:38,343 --> 01:00:41,638
Just a little personal matter
between me and Eastwood.

757
01:00:42,347 --> 01:00:43,681
This don't concern the law.

758
01:00:43,723 --> 01:00:46,643
Tonight, everything concerns the law.
Now break it up.

759
01:00:46,684 --> 01:00:50,146
Any brawling, it's 15
days in the county jail.

760
01:00:50,188 --> 01:00:54,526
All right, folks. Come on, this is a party.
Come on! Let's have some fun!

761
01:00:59,697 --> 01:01:01,950
8:00 Monday, runt.

762
01:01:02,033 --> 01:01:07,372
If you ain't here, I'll hunt you
and shoot you down like a duck.

763
01:01:07,455 --> 01:01:10,667
It's "dog," Buford.
Shoot him down like a dog.

764
01:01:10,708 --> 01:01:15,380
Let's go, boys!
Let these sissies have their party!

765
01:01:16,589 --> 01:01:19,050
Marty, what are you doing,
saying you're gonna meet Tannen?

766
01:01:19,133 --> 01:01:21,177
Hey, Doc, Doc, don't worry about it.

767
01:01:21,219 --> 01:01:23,721
Monday morning 8:00 a.m.
We're gonna be gone, right?

768
01:01:23,763 --> 01:01:26,724
Theoretically, yes,
but what if the train's late?

769
01:01:26,808 --> 01:01:28,226
- Late?
-We'll discuss this later.

770
01:01:28,309 --> 01:01:29,519
No, we'll discuss it now. Late?
What do you mean?

771
01:01:29,561 --> 01:01:31,488
Thank you for your
gallantry, Mr. Eastwood.

772
01:01:31,500 --> 01:01:32,146
Hey, ma'am.

773
01:01:32,230 --> 01:01:34,566
Had you not interceded,
Emmett might have been shot.

774
01:01:34,649 --> 01:01:37,402
Marty... Clint, I'm gonna take Clara home.

775
01:01:37,485 --> 01:01:39,073
Right. Good night,
Doc. Good night, Clara.

776
01:01:39,085 --> 01:01:40,613
You sure set him
straight, Mr. Eastwood.

777
01:01:40,697 --> 01:01:43,575
I'm glad somebody finally got the gumption
to stand up to that son of a bitch.

778
01:01:43,616 --> 01:01:46,411
You're all right in my book, Mr. Eastwood.
I'd like to buy you a drink.

779
01:01:46,452 --> 01:01:47,495
Hey, listen, I don't want a drink.

780
01:01:47,579 --> 01:01:49,247
- You don't have to buy me anything.
-Young man. Young man.

781
01:01:49,330 --> 01:01:51,291
- It was no big deal.
-I'd like for you to have this brand-new

782
01:01:51,374 --> 01:01:54,419
Colt Peacemaker and gun belt
free of charge.

783
01:01:55,753 --> 01:01:58,339
- Free?
-I want everybody to know

784
01:01:58,423 --> 01:02:02,218
that the gun that shot Buford Tannen
was a Colt Peacemaker!

785
01:02:02,260 --> 01:02:05,096
Hey, no problem. Thanks a lot.

786
01:02:05,138 --> 01:02:09,017
Of course you understand that if you lose,
I'm taking it back.

787
01:02:12,270 --> 01:02:13,730
Thanks again.

788
01:02:17,025 --> 01:02:19,861
You had him, Mr. Eastwood.
You could have just walked away,

789
01:02:19,944 --> 01:02:22,196
and nobody would have thought
the less of you for it.

790
01:02:22,280 --> 01:02:26,451
All it would have been was words,
hot air from a buffoon.

791
01:02:26,534 --> 01:02:28,244
Instead, you let him rile you.

792
01:02:28,286 --> 01:02:32,373
Rile you into playing his game,
his way, by his rules.

793
01:02:32,457 --> 01:02:34,792
Seamus, relax. I know what I'm doing.

794
01:02:34,876 --> 01:02:36,961
- He reminds me of poor Martin.
-Aye.

795
01:02:37,045 --> 01:02:38,254
- Who?
-Me brother.

796
01:02:38,296 --> 01:02:41,466
Wait a minute. Wait a minute.
You have a brother named Martin McFly?

797
01:02:41,549 --> 01:02:43,968
Had a brother.

798
01:02:44,052 --> 01:02:46,763
Martin used to let men provoke him
into fighting.

799
01:02:46,804 --> 01:02:49,724
He was concerned that people
would think him a coward if he refused.

800
01:02:49,807 --> 01:02:52,143
That's how he got a Bowie knife
shoved through his belly

801
01:02:52,226 --> 01:02:55,146
in a saloon in Virginia City.

802
01:02:55,188 --> 01:02:59,025
Never considered the future, poor Martin.
God rest his soul.

803
01:03:00,526 --> 01:03:04,364
Sure, and I hope you're considering
the future, Mr. Eastwood.

804
01:03:07,659 --> 01:03:10,119
I think about it all the time.

805
01:03:10,995 --> 01:03:12,705
And that crater
in the middle north west,

806
01:03:12,789 --> 01:03:14,832
the one that's out there
all by itself like a starburst...

807
01:03:14,874 --> 01:03:15,917
Uh-huh.

808
01:03:16,000 --> 01:03:18,252
...that one's called Copernicus.

809
01:03:19,170 --> 01:03:21,714
Listen to me. I feel
like I'm teaching school.

810
01:03:22,882 --> 01:03:25,343
Please, continue the lesson.

811
01:03:25,385 --> 01:03:28,388
I never found lunar geography
so fascinating.

812
01:03:28,471 --> 01:03:30,598
You're quite knowledgeable.

813
01:03:30,682 --> 01:03:34,519
When I was 11, I had diphtheria.
I was quarantined for three months.

814
01:03:34,560 --> 01:03:38,147
So my father brought this telescope,
and he put it next to my bed

815
01:03:38,189 --> 01:03:40,817
so I could see everything out the window.

816
01:03:41,985 --> 01:03:45,238
Emmett, do you think we'll ever be able
to travel to the moon

817
01:03:45,321 --> 01:03:48,408
the way we travel across the country
on trains?

818
01:03:48,491 --> 01:03:51,911
Definitely. Although not for 84 years
and not on trains.

819
01:03:51,995 --> 01:03:55,873
We'll have space vehicles,
capsules sent aloft with rockets.

820
01:03:55,915 --> 01:04:00,253
Devices that create giant explosions.
Explosions so powerful that they just...

821
01:04:00,336 --> 01:04:02,463
That they break the pull
of the Earth's gravity

822
01:04:02,547 --> 01:04:05,758
and send the projectile
through outer space.

823
01:04:07,218 --> 01:04:09,554
Emmett, I read that book, too!

824
01:04:09,637 --> 01:04:13,224
You're quoting Jules Verne
From the Earth to the Moon.

825
01:04:13,266 --> 01:04:15,560
You've read Jules Verne?

826
01:04:16,310 --> 01:04:18,229
I adore Jules Verne.

827
01:04:18,312 --> 01:04:19,939
So do I.

828
01:04:20,023 --> 01:04:22,900
Twenty Thousand Leagues Under the Sea.
My absolute favorite.

829
01:04:22,984 --> 01:04:24,902
The first time I read that
when I was a little boy,

830
01:04:24,986 --> 01:04:27,572
why, I wanted to meet Captain Nemo.

831
01:04:27,655 --> 01:04:30,825
Don't tease, Emmett. You couldn't have
read that when you were a boy.

832
01:04:30,908 --> 01:04:33,286
It was only first published 10 years ago.

833
01:04:33,619 --> 01:04:37,498
Oh, yes. Well, I meant it made me
feel like a boy.

834
01:04:39,709 --> 01:04:44,338
I never met a woman
who liked Jules Verne before.

835
01:04:46,382 --> 01:04:49,802
I never ever met a man like you before.

836
01:05:42,188 --> 01:05:43,606
Doc?

837
01:05:48,069 --> 01:05:49,195
Doc?

838
01:05:52,198 --> 01:05:54,575
Hope you know what you're doing.

839
01:06:07,839 --> 01:06:09,674
You talking to me?

840
01:06:12,343 --> 01:06:14,637
You talking to me, Tannen?

841
01:06:18,516 --> 01:06:21,102
Well, I'm the only one here.

842
01:06:21,185 --> 01:06:24,856
Go ahead, make my day.

843
01:06:31,320 --> 01:06:34,198
- Say good morning, Mr. Eastwood.
-Morning.

844
01:06:34,282 --> 01:06:35,908
Have a cigar, Mr. Eastwood.

845
01:06:35,992 --> 01:06:38,536
Anything I can do for you today,
Mr. Eastwood?

846
01:06:38,578 --> 01:06:41,747
- No, that's fine.
-Good luck tomorrow, Mr. Eastwood.

847
01:06:41,831 --> 01:06:44,542
- We'll be praying for you.
-Thanks.

848
01:06:45,877 --> 01:06:50,047
Good morning, Mr. Eastwood.
Interest you in a new suit for tomorrow?

849
01:06:52,049 --> 01:06:54,051
I'm fine. Thanks.

850
01:07:05,271 --> 01:07:08,733
- Doc, what are you doing?
-Oh, nothing.

851
01:07:08,816 --> 01:07:11,402
I was just out enjoying the morning air.

852
01:07:11,485 --> 01:07:13,863
It's really lovely here in the morning.
Don't you think?

853
01:07:13,905 --> 01:07:14,947
Yeah, it's lovely, Doc.

854
01:07:15,031 --> 01:07:17,950
So listen, we've got to load the DeLorean
up and get ready to roll, all right?

855
01:07:18,034 --> 01:07:20,536
Hey, look at that, the tombstone.

856
01:07:22,246 --> 01:07:25,124
Marty, let me see that photograph again.

857
01:07:27,001 --> 01:07:29,754
My name, it's vanished.

858
01:07:29,837 --> 01:07:32,215
Hey, that's great, Doc. Don't you get it?

859
01:07:32,256 --> 01:07:34,759
We're going back to the future tomorrow,
so everything's being erased.

860
01:07:34,842 --> 01:07:36,677
But only my name is erased.

861
01:07:36,761 --> 01:07:38,512
The tombstone itself
and the date still remain.

862
01:07:38,596 --> 01:07:40,473
That doesn't make sense.

863
01:07:40,556 --> 01:07:43,142
We know that this photograph represents
what will happen

864
01:07:43,226 --> 01:07:46,604
if the events of today continue
to run their course into tomorrow.

865
01:07:46,646 --> 01:07:48,981
- Right. So?
-Excuse me, Mr. Eastwood.

866
01:07:49,065 --> 01:07:50,783
I just need to take
your measurements.

867
01:07:50,795 --> 01:07:52,693
Oh, look, pal, I don't
want to buy a suit.

868
01:07:53,819 --> 01:07:57,114
- No, this is for your coffin.
-My coffin?

869
01:07:57,156 --> 01:07:59,617
Well, the odds are running
two to one against you.

870
01:07:59,700 --> 01:08:02,036
Might as well be prepared.

871
01:08:02,119 --> 01:08:05,581
So it may not be my name that's
supposed to end up on this tombstone.

872
01:08:05,623 --> 01:08:07,375
It may be yours.

873
01:08:08,626 --> 01:08:10,753
- Great Scott.
-I know. This is heavy.

874
01:08:10,795 --> 01:08:12,797
Marty, why are you wearing that gun?

875
01:08:12,838 --> 01:08:14,966
You're not considering going up
against Tannen tomorrow?

876
01:08:15,007 --> 01:08:17,843
Doc, tomorrow morning
I'm going back to the future with you.

877
01:08:17,927 --> 01:08:21,389
But if Buford Tannen comes looking
for trouble, I'm gonna be ready for him.

878
01:08:21,472 --> 01:08:23,808
You heard what
that son of a bitch called me last night.

879
01:08:23,891 --> 01:08:26,686
Marty, you can't go losing your judgment
every time someone calls you a name.

880
01:08:26,769 --> 01:08:31,148
That's exactly what causes you
to get into that accident in the future.

881
01:08:32,775 --> 01:08:36,195
What? What about my future?

882
01:08:36,279 --> 01:08:39,448
I can't tell you. It might
make things worse.

883
01:08:39,490 --> 01:08:43,327
Wait a minute.
Doc, what is wrong with my future?

884
01:08:44,203 --> 01:08:48,916
Marty, we all have to make decisions
that affect the course of our lives.

885
01:08:49,000 --> 01:08:53,796
You've got to do what you've got to do,
and I've got to do what I've got to do.

886
01:09:05,349 --> 01:09:07,351
- Marty.
-Yeah.

887
01:09:07,435 --> 01:09:09,228
- I've made a decision.
-Uh-huh.

888
01:09:09,312 --> 01:09:10,396
I'm not going with you tomorrow.

889
01:09:11,522 --> 01:09:13,232
I'm staying here.

890
01:09:16,610 --> 01:09:19,488
What are you talking about, Doc?

891
01:09:19,530 --> 01:09:21,407
There's no point in denying it.

892
01:09:21,490 --> 01:09:24,035
- I'm in love with Clara.
-Oh, man.

893
01:09:24,118 --> 01:09:28,205
Doc, we don't belong here.
Neither one of us.

894
01:09:28,289 --> 01:09:31,208
You know, it could still be you
that gets shot tomorrow.

895
01:09:31,250 --> 01:09:33,836
This tombstone could
still be in your future.

896
01:09:33,878 --> 01:09:37,214
Marty, the future isn't written.

897
01:09:37,298 --> 01:09:39,717
It can be changed. You know that.

898
01:09:41,135 --> 01:09:44,847
Anyone can make their future
whatever they want it to be.

899
01:09:44,889 --> 01:09:49,268
I can't let this one little photograph
determine my entire destiny.

900
01:09:49,352 --> 01:09:54,523
I have to live my life according
to what I believe is right in my heart.

901
01:09:56,859 --> 01:09:59,737
Doc, you're a scientist.

902
01:10:01,697 --> 01:10:06,243
So you tell me.
What's the right thing to do up here?

903
01:10:20,049 --> 01:10:21,467
You're right, Marty.

904
01:10:44,323 --> 01:10:48,494
- Wow, that worked great.
-I've at least got to tell her goodbye.

905
01:10:49,412 --> 01:10:53,833
Come on, Doc. Think about it.
What are you gonna say to her?

906
01:10:53,916 --> 01:10:55,334
"I've got to go back to the future?"

907
01:10:55,418 --> 01:10:57,711
I mean,
she's not gonna understand that, Doc.

908
01:10:57,795 --> 01:11:01,465
Hell, I'm in it with you,
and I don't even understand it.

909
01:11:04,009 --> 01:11:06,971
Doc, listen.

910
01:11:08,264 --> 01:11:09,890
Maybe we...

911
01:11:09,974 --> 01:11:13,310
I don't know,
maybe we can just take Clara with us.

912
01:11:14,395 --> 01:11:15,980
To the future?

913
01:11:20,192 --> 01:11:25,656
As you reminded me, Marty, I'm a scientist,
so I must be scientific about this.

914
01:11:25,698 --> 01:11:27,533
I cautioned you
about disrupting the continuum

915
01:11:27,616 --> 01:11:31,328
for your own personal benefit.
Therefore, I must do no less.

916
01:11:31,370 --> 01:11:34,582
We shall proceed as planned,
and as soon as we return to 1985,

917
01:11:34,665 --> 01:11:38,169
we'll destroy this infernal machine.

918
01:11:38,210 --> 01:11:41,672
Traveling through time
has become much too painful.

919
01:12:12,077 --> 01:12:13,871
It's Emmett, Clara.

920
01:12:17,958 --> 01:12:20,711
Emmett, won't you come in?

921
01:12:20,794 --> 01:12:23,923
No, I better not. I...

922
01:12:26,217 --> 01:12:27,468
What's wrong?

923
01:12:29,011 --> 01:12:30,554
I've come to say goodbye.

924
01:12:32,348 --> 01:12:34,808
Goodbye? Well, where are you going?

925
01:12:35,518 --> 01:12:40,147
I'm going away. And well, I'm
afraid I'll never see you again.

926
01:12:41,690 --> 01:12:43,025
Emmett!

927
01:12:43,067 --> 01:12:48,280
Clara, I want you to know
that I care about you deeply.

928
01:12:49,323 --> 01:12:54,745
But I've realized that I don't belong here,
and I have to go back where I came from.

929
01:12:54,828 --> 01:12:57,414
And where might that be?

930
01:12:57,456 --> 01:12:59,166
I can't tell you.

931
01:13:01,460 --> 01:13:05,256
Well, wherever you're going,
take me with you.

932
01:13:06,590 --> 01:13:08,884
I can't, Clara.

933
01:13:08,926 --> 01:13:11,929
I wish it didn't have to be this way,
but just believe me when I tell you

934
01:13:11,971 --> 01:13:16,433
that I'll never forget
you and that I love you.

935
01:13:18,602 --> 01:13:20,854
I don't understand
what you're trying to say.

936
01:13:20,938 --> 01:13:24,817
Clara, I don't think there's any way
that you can understand it.

937
01:13:25,526 --> 01:13:27,945
Please, Emmett. Please, I have to know.

938
01:13:27,987 --> 01:13:31,073
If you sincerely do love me,
then tell me the truth.

939
01:13:33,117 --> 01:13:34,785
All right then.

940
01:13:35,828 --> 01:13:37,079
I'm from the future.

941
01:13:39,123 --> 01:13:42,126
I came here in a time machine
that I invented,

942
01:13:42,209 --> 01:13:46,297
and tomorrow I have to go back
to the year 1985.

943
01:13:52,511 --> 01:13:53,971
Yes, Emmett.

944
01:13:55,347 --> 01:13:57,016
I do understand.

945
01:13:59,602 --> 01:14:04,315
I understand that because you know
I'm partial to the writings of Jules Verne,

946
01:14:04,398 --> 01:14:07,943
you concocted those mendacities
in order to take advantage of me.

947
01:14:08,944 --> 01:14:11,363
Oh! I've heard some whoppers in my day,

948
01:14:11,447 --> 01:14:13,991
but the fact that you'd expect me
to entertain a notion like that

949
01:14:14,033 --> 01:14:16,785
is so insulting and degrading!

950
01:14:18,579 --> 01:14:22,541
All you had to say is, "I don't love you,
and I don't want to see you anymore."

951
01:14:22,625 --> 01:14:25,085
That, at least, would have been respectful!

952
01:14:25,836 --> 01:14:27,212
But that's not the truth.

953
01:15:06,835 --> 01:15:08,712
Good to see you, too.

954
01:15:10,047 --> 01:15:13,550
Emmett. What can I get you? The usual?

955
01:15:13,634 --> 01:15:17,429
No, Chester, I'm gonna need something
a lot stronger than that tonight.

956
01:15:17,513 --> 01:15:20,391
- Sarsaparilla.
-Whiskey, Chester.

957
01:15:21,266 --> 01:15:23,727
Whiskey? Emmett, are you sure?

958
01:15:23,769 --> 01:15:26,105
You know what happened to you
on the Fourth of July.

959
01:15:26,188 --> 01:15:27,398
Whiskey.

960
01:15:28,774 --> 01:15:32,027
Okay, I ain't your papa.

961
01:15:32,069 --> 01:15:35,322
Just don't want to see you
do the wrong thing.

962
01:15:36,657 --> 01:15:38,701
You can leave the bottle.

963
01:15:40,577 --> 01:15:42,371
It's a woman, right?

964
01:15:44,081 --> 01:15:46,291
I knew it.
I have seen that look on a man's face

965
01:15:46,375 --> 01:15:49,253
a thousand times all across the country.

966
01:15:49,336 --> 01:15:51,755
All I can tell you, friend,
is you'll get over her.

967
01:15:51,797 --> 01:15:55,217
Oh... Clara was one in a million.

968
01:15:56,260 --> 01:16:00,556
One in a billion. One in a googolplex.

969
01:16:00,597 --> 01:16:04,226
The woman of my dreams,
and I've lost her for all time.

970
01:16:05,519 --> 01:16:08,981
I can assure you, sir,
there are other women.

971
01:16:09,064 --> 01:16:11,734
Why, if peddling this barbed wire
all across the country

972
01:16:11,775 --> 01:16:14,111
has taught me one thing for certain,

973
01:16:14,194 --> 01:16:17,156
is that you never know
what the future might bring.

974
01:16:17,239 --> 01:16:21,118
The future.
Oh, I can tell you about the future.

975
01:16:31,628 --> 01:16:33,547
Oh, man, did I sleep.

976
01:16:36,592 --> 01:16:38,469
What time is it, Doc?

977
01:16:42,431 --> 01:16:43,640
Doc?

978
01:16:54,985 --> 01:16:56,195
Wake up!

979
01:16:57,946 --> 01:16:59,865
Get up! Let's go!

980
01:17:01,116 --> 01:17:03,160
I got me a runt to kill.

981
01:17:03,202 --> 01:17:06,163
It's still early, boss. What's your hurry?

982
01:17:07,206 --> 01:17:08,499
I'm hungry.

983
01:17:09,291 --> 01:17:12,336
And in the future, we don't need horses.

984
01:17:14,046 --> 01:17:17,508
We have motorized carriages
called automobiles.

985
01:17:18,675 --> 01:17:22,012
If everybody's got
one of these auto whatsits,

986
01:17:22,095 --> 01:17:24,515
does anybody walk or run anymore?

987
01:17:25,182 --> 01:17:29,144
Of course we run,
but for recreation, for fun.

988
01:17:29,186 --> 01:17:32,856
Run for fun?
What the hell kind of fun is that?

989
01:17:43,116 --> 01:17:45,369
Doc! Doc!

990
01:17:52,209 --> 01:17:54,002
How much has he had?

991
01:17:54,044 --> 01:17:57,381
None. That's the first one,
and he hasn't touched it yet.

992
01:17:58,215 --> 01:17:59,842
He just likes to hold it.

993
01:18:03,303 --> 01:18:06,265
Doc! Doc! What are you doing?

994
01:18:07,266 --> 01:18:10,561
I've lost her, Marty.
There's nothing left for me here.

995
01:18:10,644 --> 01:18:12,563
All right, that's why you gotta come back
with me.

996
01:18:12,646 --> 01:18:14,898
- Where?
-Back to the future!

997
01:18:19,194 --> 01:18:22,322
- Right! Let's get going!
-Great.

998
01:18:22,406 --> 01:18:25,576
Gentlemen, excuse me,
but my friend and I have to catch a train.

999
01:18:25,617 --> 01:18:27,369
Here's to you, blacksmith.

1000
01:18:27,411 --> 01:18:29,830
- And to the future.
-Amen.

1001
01:18:30,289 --> 01:18:31,874
- Amen.
-Emmett, no!

1002
01:18:40,090 --> 01:18:43,010
Doc! Doc! Doc!

1003
01:18:43,927 --> 01:18:46,972
Come on, Doc. Wake up. Wake up, Doc!

1004
01:18:48,015 --> 01:18:50,225
- How many did he have?
-Just the one.

1005
01:18:50,267 --> 01:18:52,436
Just the one? Come on, Doc.

1006
01:18:52,477 --> 01:18:54,771
There's a fellow that
can't hold his liquor.

1007
01:18:54,813 --> 01:18:57,691
- Get me some coffee. Black!
-Joey, coffee!

1008
01:19:07,701 --> 01:19:09,828
Ma'am?

1009
01:19:09,912 --> 01:19:14,291
- How far does the 8:00 train go?
-San Francisco is the end of the line.

1010
01:19:15,918 --> 01:19:18,086
I'll take a one-way ticket.

1011
01:19:19,463 --> 01:19:21,465
You want to sober him up in a hurry, son,

1012
01:19:21,548 --> 01:19:23,550
you're gonna have to use something
a lot stronger than coffee.

1013
01:19:23,634 --> 01:19:26,261
Yeah, what do you suggest?

1014
01:19:26,303 --> 01:19:29,723
Joey, let's make some wake-up juice.

1015
01:19:29,806 --> 01:19:32,309
Come on, Doc, swallow. Here we go.

1016
01:19:37,356 --> 01:19:42,486
In about 10 minutes, he's gonna be
as sober as a priest on Sunday.

1017
01:19:43,487 --> 01:19:44,655
Ten minutes!

1018
01:19:44,738 --> 01:19:47,199
Why do we have to cut these things
so damn close?

1019
01:19:47,282 --> 01:19:49,993
Here, stick this clothespin on his nose.

1020
01:19:51,870 --> 01:19:57,501
When he opens up his mouth,
go ahead and pour it on down his gullet.

1021
01:19:57,584 --> 01:19:59,336
Oh, and stand back.

1022
01:20:17,771 --> 01:20:21,066
- He's still out!
-Oh, that? That was just a reflex action.

1023
01:20:21,149 --> 01:20:24,528
It's gonna take a few more minutes
for the stuff to really clear up his head.

1024
01:20:24,569 --> 01:20:25,779
Perfect.

1025
01:20:47,050 --> 01:20:49,219
Come on, Doc.
Come on, wake up, buddy.

1026
01:20:49,261 --> 01:20:52,180
Wake up, Doc! Come on. Come on.

1027
01:20:52,222 --> 01:20:54,850
Seamus, wouldn't expect
to see you here this morning.

1028
01:20:54,891 --> 01:20:58,854
Aye. Something inside me told me
I should be here

1029
01:20:59,896 --> 01:21:03,025
as if my future had
something to do with it.

1030
01:21:04,735 --> 01:21:07,195
He'll come around in a minute. Come on.

1031
01:21:07,237 --> 01:21:11,241
Come on, Doc. Let's go, Doc!
Let's wake up now, buddy. Come on.

1032
01:21:18,248 --> 01:21:20,542
Are you in there, Eastwood?

1033
01:21:22,461 --> 01:21:25,547
It's 8:00, and I'm calling you out.

1034
01:21:30,469 --> 01:21:32,137
It's not 8:00 yet!

1035
01:21:32,596 --> 01:21:34,556
It is by my watch!

1036
01:21:34,598 --> 01:21:37,517
Let's settle this once and for all, runt!

1037
01:21:39,227 --> 01:21:41,521
Or ain't you got the gumption?

1038
01:21:50,989 --> 01:21:52,282
Listen.

1039
01:21:54,743 --> 01:21:57,621
I'm not really feeling up to this today.

1040
01:21:59,164 --> 01:22:00,791
So I'm gonna have to forfeit.

1041
01:22:01,458 --> 01:22:03,794
Forfeit?

1042
01:22:04,377 --> 01:22:06,129
What's that mean?

1043
01:22:07,506 --> 01:22:11,426
- It means that you win without a fight.
-Without shooting? He can't do that.

1044
01:22:11,468 --> 01:22:13,637
Hey, you can't do that!

1045
01:22:13,678 --> 01:22:15,222
You know what I think?

1046
01:22:15,305 --> 01:22:18,642
I think you ain't nothing
but a gutless, yellow turd!

1047
01:22:18,683 --> 01:22:23,355
And I'm giving you to the count of 10
to come out here and prove I'm wrong!

1048
01:22:24,272 --> 01:22:25,607
One!

1049
01:22:25,649 --> 01:22:28,276
Doc, come on, sober up, buddy.
Let's go. Come on.

1050
01:22:28,318 --> 01:22:30,737
- Two!
- You better get out there, son.

1051
01:22:30,821 --> 01:22:33,949
I got $20 gold bet on you,
so don't let me down.

1052
01:22:33,990 --> 01:22:35,200
Three!

1053
01:22:35,283 --> 01:22:39,496
I got $30 gold bet against you,
so don't let me down.

1054
01:22:39,579 --> 01:22:40,622
Four!

1055
01:22:40,664 --> 01:22:45,168
You better face up to it, son,
because if you don't go out there...

1056
01:22:45,210 --> 01:22:46,670
- What?
-Five!

1057
01:22:48,171 --> 01:22:51,133
- What if I don't go out there?
-You're a coward.

1058
01:22:51,174 --> 01:22:52,300
Six!

1059
01:22:52,342 --> 01:22:55,512
And you'll be branded a coward
for the rest of your days!

1060
01:22:55,595 --> 01:22:59,724
Everybody everywhere
will say Clint Eastwood

1061
01:22:59,808 --> 01:23:02,519
is the biggest yellow belly in the West!

1062
01:23:07,649 --> 01:23:08,692
Seven!

1063
01:23:09,734 --> 01:23:10,861
Here!

1064
01:23:14,990 --> 01:23:16,158
Eight!

1065
01:23:25,000 --> 01:23:26,209
I already got a gun.

1066
01:23:28,295 --> 01:23:29,546
Nine!

1067
01:23:34,384 --> 01:23:35,427
Ten!

1068
01:23:40,557 --> 01:23:42,225
Do you hear me, runt?

1069
01:23:42,309 --> 01:23:46,521
I said that's 10, you gutless,
yellow pie-slinger!

1070
01:23:50,233 --> 01:23:52,485
He's an asshole!

1071
01:23:52,569 --> 01:23:54,529
I don't care what Tannen says!

1072
01:23:54,571 --> 01:23:57,532
And I don't care
what anybody else says either.

1073
01:23:58,658 --> 01:24:01,161
- Doc! Doc, you okay?
-I think so.

1074
01:24:02,370 --> 01:24:03,872
What a headache!

1075
01:24:03,914 --> 01:24:05,752
Listen, you got a
back door to this place?

1076
01:24:05,764 --> 01:24:06,833
Yeah, it's in the back.

1077
01:24:06,917 --> 01:24:07,918
Let's go, Doc.

1078
01:24:08,001 --> 01:24:11,546
Are you coming out here,
or do I have to come in after you?

1079
01:24:13,465 --> 01:24:15,425
The thing I really miss here is Tylenol.

1080
01:24:16,259 --> 01:24:17,427
Hey!

1081
01:24:23,433 --> 01:24:24,935
Reach, blacksmith!

1082
01:24:41,952 --> 01:24:44,621
Yes, sir, that poor fellow last night

1083
01:24:44,704 --> 01:24:48,667
had the worst case of broken heart
I have ever seen.

1084
01:24:48,750 --> 01:24:51,795
When he said he didn't know
how he could live the rest of his life

1085
01:24:51,878 --> 01:24:54,673
knowing how much hurt
he'd caused that little girl.

1086
01:24:54,756 --> 01:24:58,802
Well, I really felt for
him. I did. Right here.

1087
01:25:03,640 --> 01:25:05,392
Listen up, Eastwood!

1088
01:25:05,475 --> 01:25:08,895
I aim to shoot somebody today,
and I prefer it'd be you.

1089
01:25:08,979 --> 01:25:11,481
But if you're just too damn yellow,

1090
01:25:11,564 --> 01:25:14,025
I guess it'll just have to be
your blacksmith friend.

1091
01:25:14,109 --> 01:25:16,528
Forget about me, Marty, and save yourself!

1092
01:25:21,574 --> 01:25:26,162
You got one minute to decide.
You hear me, runt? One minute!

1093
01:25:29,332 --> 01:25:32,335
I've never seen a man so broken up
over a woman.

1094
01:25:32,419 --> 01:25:35,046
What did he say her name was? Cara? Sara?

1095
01:25:35,130 --> 01:25:36,673
- Clara.
-Clara.

1096
01:25:40,010 --> 01:25:41,720
- Excuse me.
-Ma'am?

1097
01:25:42,887 --> 01:25:46,224
But was this man tall
with great big, brown puppy-dog eyes

1098
01:25:46,308 --> 01:25:48,852
and long silvery, flowing hair?

1099
01:25:48,893 --> 01:25:50,103
You know him.

1100
01:25:52,981 --> 01:25:54,065
Emmett!

1101
01:26:08,913 --> 01:26:10,790
Time's up, runt!

1102
01:26:16,880 --> 01:26:19,716
Prepare to meet your maker, blacksmith.

1103
01:26:19,799 --> 01:26:21,593
Right here, Tannen!

1104
01:26:59,422 --> 01:27:00,423
Draw!

1105
01:27:03,760 --> 01:27:04,886
No!

1106
01:27:20,485 --> 01:27:23,029
I thought we could settle this like men.

1107
01:27:24,572 --> 01:27:26,616
You thought wrong, dude.

1108
01:27:48,763 --> 01:27:50,223
Thank you.

1109
01:28:53,786 --> 01:28:55,538
That was good.

1110
01:28:58,333 --> 01:29:00,335
- You know what I think?
-No.

1111
01:29:00,376 --> 01:29:02,795
- I think Buford's going to jail.
-Yeah.

1112
01:29:08,468 --> 01:29:10,553
Get him out of that shit.

1113
01:29:10,637 --> 01:29:12,180
Get them!

1114
01:29:16,226 --> 01:29:20,855
Buford Tannen, you're under arrest
for robbing the Pine City stage.

1115
01:29:20,897 --> 01:29:23,024
You got anything to say?

1116
01:29:28,196 --> 01:29:30,031
I hate manure.

1117
01:29:30,073 --> 01:29:31,115
Look!

1118
01:29:34,869 --> 01:29:36,120
Yes!

1119
01:29:37,580 --> 01:29:39,916
- The train!
-Can we make it?

1120
01:29:39,958 --> 01:29:41,876
We'll have to cut them off at Coyote Pass.

1121
01:29:44,379 --> 01:29:47,215
Hey! Hey, mister. Mr. Eastwood.

1122
01:29:47,257 --> 01:29:49,717
- Here's your gun, mister.
-Thanks, kid.

1123
01:29:55,098 --> 01:29:56,766
Seamus!

1124
01:29:57,892 --> 01:29:59,852
It's worth $12. Never been used.

1125
01:30:01,271 --> 01:30:05,775
- Maybe I'll trade it for a new hat.
-Right, and take care of that baby!

1126
01:30:06,985 --> 01:30:08,278
I will!

1127
01:30:14,951 --> 01:30:16,202
Emmett!

1128
01:30:18,621 --> 01:30:19,831
Emmett!

1129
01:30:21,291 --> 01:30:22,584
Emmett!

1130
01:30:27,422 --> 01:30:29,132
"Time machine."

1131
01:31:12,550 --> 01:31:13,551
Come on, Marty!

1132
01:31:17,305 --> 01:31:20,183
- Go, Doc.
-Come on. Give me your hand!

1133
01:31:55,635 --> 01:31:57,053
Come on, Marty.

1134
01:32:01,557 --> 01:32:03,059
Come on. Let's go!

1135
01:32:11,734 --> 01:32:13,069
Masks on.

1136
01:32:28,209 --> 01:32:30,670
- Reach!
-Is this a holdup?

1137
01:32:32,672 --> 01:32:35,091
It's a science experiment.

1138
01:32:35,174 --> 01:32:38,010
Stop the train just before you hit
the switch track up ahead.

1139
01:32:53,860 --> 01:32:56,946
- Doc!
-Uncouple the cars from the tender!

1140
01:33:23,806 --> 01:33:25,266
I've wanted to do that all my life.

1141
01:33:59,759 --> 01:34:01,010
What are these things, anyway?

1142
01:34:01,093 --> 01:34:02,970
My own version of Pres-to-Logs.

1143
01:34:03,012 --> 01:34:04,654
Compressed wood
with anthracite dust

1144
01:34:04,666 --> 01:34:06,766
chemically treated to
burn hotter and longer.

1145
01:34:06,849 --> 01:34:09,227
I use them in my forge
so I don't have to stoke it.

1146
01:34:09,310 --> 01:34:11,354
These three in the furnace
will ignite sequentially,

1147
01:34:11,395 --> 01:34:14,106
make the fire burn hotter,
kick up the boiler pressure,

1148
01:34:14,190 --> 01:34:15,525
and make the train go faster.

1149
01:34:27,411 --> 01:34:29,247
Ready to roll!

1150
01:35:00,903 --> 01:35:02,238
Emmett!

1151
01:35:06,868 --> 01:35:09,370
Marty, are the time circuits on?

1152
01:35:10,538 --> 01:35:11,539
Check, Doc!

1153
01:35:12,206 --> 01:35:14,292
Input the destination time.

1154
01:35:14,375 --> 01:35:18,087
October 27, 1985, 11:00 a.m.

1155
01:35:19,505 --> 01:35:23,885
Check. Okay, we're cruising
at a steady 25 miles an hour, Doc.

1156
01:35:23,926 --> 01:35:25,720
I'm throwing in the Pres-to-Logs.

1157
01:35:35,396 --> 01:35:38,900
Marty, the new gauge on the dashboard
will tell us the boiler temperature.

1158
01:35:38,941 --> 01:35:42,361
It's color-coded to indicate
when each log will fire.

1159
01:35:42,445 --> 01:35:43,946
Green, yellow and red.

1160
01:35:44,780 --> 01:35:48,284
Each detonation will be accompanied
by a sudden burst of acceleration.

1161
01:35:50,453 --> 01:35:55,291
Hopefully, we'll hit 88 miles per hour
before the needle gets much past 2,000.

1162
01:35:55,374 --> 01:35:58,127
Why? What happens after it hits 2,000?

1163
01:35:58,169 --> 01:35:59,962
The whole boiler explodes!

1164
01:36:00,963 --> 01:36:02,006
Perfect!

1165
01:36:17,980 --> 01:36:21,817
- Hey, Doc! We just hit 35!
-Okay, Marty. I'm coming aboard!

1166
01:36:32,620 --> 01:36:33,621
Emmett!

1167
01:36:34,830 --> 01:36:36,374
Emmett!

1168
01:36:38,542 --> 01:36:40,169
Come on. Come on.

1169
01:36:49,679 --> 01:36:52,682
You better hold onto something, Doc!
The yellow log is about to blow!

1170
01:36:57,937 --> 01:36:58,980
Golly.

1171
01:37:02,692 --> 01:37:04,318
We just passed 40, Doc!

1172
01:37:26,882 --> 01:37:28,050
Emmett!

1173
01:37:29,510 --> 01:37:31,220
Emmett!

1174
01:37:37,059 --> 01:37:38,602
Emmett!

1175
01:37:41,022 --> 01:37:43,691
We just passed 45, Doc! Go for it!

1176
01:37:54,076 --> 01:37:55,077
Fifty.

1177
01:38:06,255 --> 01:38:08,340
- Emmett!
-Clara!

1178
01:38:09,341 --> 01:38:10,760
I love you!

1179
01:38:12,928 --> 01:38:18,434
- Doc! Doc! What's happening?
-It's Clara! She's on the train!

1180
01:38:19,018 --> 01:38:20,436
Clara? Perfect.

1181
01:38:21,062 --> 01:38:24,648
She's in the cab! I'm going back for her!

1182
01:38:24,732 --> 01:38:25,816
The windmill!

1183
01:38:25,900 --> 01:38:29,820
Doc! The windmill! We're going past 50!
You'll never make it!

1184
01:38:31,864 --> 01:38:36,285
Then we'll have to take her back with us!
Keep calling out the speed!

1185
01:38:36,368 --> 01:38:39,789
Clara, climb out here to me!

1186
01:38:39,830 --> 01:38:42,666
- I don't know if I can!
-You can do it!

1187
01:38:42,750 --> 01:38:44,877
Just don't look down!

1188
01:38:48,339 --> 01:38:49,632
That's it!

1189
01:39:03,813 --> 01:39:05,439
Sixty miles an hour, Doc!

1190
01:39:08,567 --> 01:39:11,737
You're doing fine! Nice and steady!

1191
01:39:15,157 --> 01:39:16,617
Come on!

1192
01:39:17,326 --> 01:39:19,453
Just a little further!

1193
01:39:19,495 --> 01:39:21,497
I can't, Emmett! I'm scared!

1194
01:39:23,958 --> 01:39:25,000
Seventy!

1195
01:39:25,960 --> 01:39:27,670
Keep coming, Clara!

1196
01:39:29,004 --> 01:39:32,049
Come on! Come on! You're doing fine!

1197
01:39:33,300 --> 01:39:37,012
Come on! Nice and easy!

1198
01:39:38,222 --> 01:39:41,058
Don't look down! That's it!
You're doing fine!

1199
01:39:44,019 --> 01:39:48,107
Doc! The red log is about to blow!

1200
01:39:55,781 --> 01:39:56,782
Clara!

1201
01:39:59,618 --> 01:40:01,328
Emmett!

1202
01:40:11,213 --> 01:40:12,882
I'm trying to reach you!

1203
01:40:12,923 --> 01:40:15,467
- Clara, hold on!
-I can't!

1204
01:40:23,559 --> 01:40:24,602
Oh!

1205
01:40:25,728 --> 01:40:27,563
Doc, I'm gonna slip you the Hoverboard!

1206
01:40:35,362 --> 01:40:36,822
Marty, watch out!

1207
01:40:45,372 --> 01:40:46,832
Emmett, help!

1208
01:40:49,543 --> 01:40:51,086
Hold on, Clara!

1209
01:40:54,423 --> 01:40:56,050
Doc, ready, Doc?

1210
01:40:57,259 --> 01:40:58,302
Catch it!

1211
01:41:00,095 --> 01:41:01,305
Yes! Yes!

1212
01:41:11,982 --> 01:41:13,275
Emmett!

1213
01:41:13,317 --> 01:41:14,735
Hold on!

1214
01:41:18,405 --> 01:41:19,406
Yes!

1215
01:43:59,858 --> 01:44:01,193
Well, Doc,

1216
01:44:02,945 --> 01:44:04,655
it's destroyed.

1217
01:44:06,907 --> 01:44:08,867
Just like you wanted.

1218
01:44:27,803 --> 01:44:30,013
- Hey, butthead, get away...
-Watch it, Biff!

1219
01:44:30,097 --> 01:44:33,350
Marty, I didn't mean to scare you.
I didn't recognize you in those clothes.

1220
01:44:33,434 --> 01:44:37,646
- What the hell are you doing?
-Just putting on the second coat now.

1221
01:44:38,814 --> 01:44:40,190
You going cowboy, huh?

1222
01:44:40,274 --> 01:44:42,985
Come on, guys.
We're gonna be late for brunch.

1223
01:44:43,026 --> 01:44:44,069
Coming, Dave.

1224
01:44:44,153 --> 01:44:47,030
Come on, Dad, we're not gonna hold
your reservations all day.

1225
01:44:47,114 --> 01:44:48,490
I can't find my glasses.

1226
01:44:48,574 --> 01:44:52,035
- Lorraine, have you seen my glasses?
-They're in your suede jacket, honey.

1227
01:44:52,119 --> 01:44:54,788
Marty, what's wrong?
We thought you went to the lake.

1228
01:44:54,830 --> 01:44:56,017
You wore that to the lake?

1229
01:44:56,029 --> 01:44:58,000
Thank God you guys
are all back to normal.

1230
01:44:58,083 --> 01:45:00,169
Marty, who are you supposed to be?
Clint Eastwood?

1231
01:45:01,420 --> 01:45:04,006
Right. I gotta go get Jennifer.

1232
01:45:08,218 --> 01:45:09,803
I really like that hat, Marty.

1233
01:45:09,845 --> 01:45:11,388
Thanks, Biff.

1234
01:45:25,819 --> 01:45:27,154
Jennifer.

1235
01:45:29,198 --> 01:45:30,407
Jen.

1236
01:45:34,703 --> 01:45:35,996
Jennifer.

1237
01:45:59,102 --> 01:46:00,395
Marty.

1238
01:46:01,772 --> 01:46:03,148
Marty.

1239
01:46:04,733 --> 01:46:06,568
I had the worst nightmare.

1240
01:46:13,033 --> 01:46:16,537
Marty, that dream I had is so real.

1241
01:46:16,578 --> 01:46:19,081
It was about the future.

1242
01:46:19,122 --> 01:46:21,124
About us.

1243
01:46:21,208 --> 01:46:23,460
And you got fired.

1244
01:46:23,544 --> 01:46:25,879
Wait a minute.
What do you mean I got fired?

1245
01:46:26,838 --> 01:46:28,048
"Hilldale."

1246
01:46:29,299 --> 01:46:32,678
Hilldale! This is where we live.

1247
01:46:32,761 --> 01:46:35,722
I mean, this is where we're going to live.

1248
01:46:37,224 --> 01:46:38,267
Someday.

1249
01:46:41,520 --> 01:46:44,773
Marty, it was a dream, wasn't it?

1250
01:46:48,610 --> 01:46:49,945
Hey.

1251
01:46:50,028 --> 01:46:52,155
The big M.

1252
01:46:52,239 --> 01:46:55,617
- How's it hanging, McFly?
-Hey, Needles.

1253
01:46:55,659 --> 01:46:59,788
Nice set of wheels.
Let's see what she can do.

1254
01:46:59,871 --> 01:47:02,124
- Next green light.
-No, thanks.

1255
01:47:03,458 --> 01:47:05,961
What's the matter? Chicken?

1256
01:47:06,461 --> 01:47:08,005
Chicken McFly.

1257
01:47:08,297 --> 01:47:09,298
Whoo!

1258
01:47:10,632 --> 01:47:13,594
- Marty, don't.
-Grab hold of something.

1259
01:47:14,595 --> 01:47:16,305
Come on! Get on!

1260
01:47:17,764 --> 01:47:19,975
Yeah, go! Go, go, go!

1261
01:47:42,581 --> 01:47:43,957
Did you do that on purpose?

1262
01:47:43,999 --> 01:47:46,501
Yeah, you think I'm stupid enough
to race that asshole?

1263
01:47:52,674 --> 01:47:55,677
Jeez! I would have hit that Rolls-Royce.

1264
01:48:05,520 --> 01:48:07,314
It erased.

1265
01:48:21,370 --> 01:48:23,246
You're right. There's not much left.

1266
01:48:25,874 --> 01:48:27,876
Doc's never coming back.

1267
01:48:42,349 --> 01:48:44,059
I'm sure gonna miss him, Jen.

1268
01:48:56,655 --> 01:48:57,739
What the hell?

1269
01:49:15,173 --> 01:49:16,299
Doc!

1270
01:49:16,800 --> 01:49:17,926
Marty!

1271
01:49:17,968 --> 01:49:20,178
Doc! Doc!

1272
01:49:20,262 --> 01:49:23,098
Marty, it runs on steam!

1273
01:49:28,395 --> 01:49:31,940
Meet the family. Clara, you know.

1274
01:49:31,982 --> 01:49:34,317
- Hi, Marty!
-Ma'am!

1275
01:49:35,360 --> 01:49:37,529
These are our boys.

1276
01:49:38,321 --> 01:49:42,117
Jules and Verne.

1277
01:49:45,245 --> 01:49:48,081
Boys, this is Marty and Jennifer.

1278
01:49:51,126 --> 01:49:53,086
Doc, I thought I'd never see you again.

1279
01:49:53,128 --> 01:49:55,380
You can't keep a good scientist down.

1280
01:49:55,464 --> 01:49:57,591
After all, I had to come back for Einstein,

1281
01:49:57,632 --> 01:50:00,969
and, well, I didn't want you
to be worried about me.

1282
01:50:01,595 --> 01:50:02,596
Oh!

1283
01:50:03,013 --> 01:50:05,474
I brought you a little souvenir.

1284
01:50:22,157 --> 01:50:25,327
It's great, Doc. Thanks.

1285
01:50:27,704 --> 01:50:31,541
Dr. Brown, I brought this note
back from the future,

1286
01:50:31,625 --> 01:50:33,877
and now it's erased.

1287
01:50:33,960 --> 01:50:35,921
Of course it's erased.

1288
01:50:37,839 --> 01:50:39,174
But what does that mean?

1289
01:50:39,257 --> 01:50:43,178
It means your future
hasn't been written yet.

1290
01:50:43,220 --> 01:50:45,013
No one's has.

1291
01:50:45,055 --> 01:50:50,101
Your future is whatever you make it.
So make it a good one, both of you.

1292
01:50:53,230 --> 01:50:54,481
We will, Doc!

1293
01:50:54,523 --> 01:50:56,066
Stand back!

1294
01:50:56,566 --> 01:50:58,693
All right, boys, buckle up!

1295
01:51:03,657 --> 01:51:08,829
Hey, Doc, where are you going now?
Back to the future?

1296
01:51:09,412 --> 01:51:12,707
No, already been there.

1297
01:51:42,487 --> 01:51:47,784
THE END

